WEBVTT

00:02.169 --> 00:05.130
<i>[tense music]</i>

00:05.130 --> 00:12.179
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:14.056 --> 00:17.100
[birds chirping]

00:17.100 --> 00:24.107
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:38.205 --> 00:41.917
<i>[faint drumming]</i>

00:46.171 --> 00:49.132
[twigs snapping]

00:49.132 --> 00:52.803
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:52.803 --> 00:53.804
[gunshot]

00:53.804 --> 00:55.555
[man grunts]

00:55.555 --> 00:57.349
[gunfire]

00:57.349 --> 00:59.643
[gunshot]

00:59.643 --> 01:01.144
‐ Rebs!

01:01.144 --> 01:02.729
[gunshots]

01:02.729 --> 01:04.398
[men grunt]

01:04.398 --> 01:07.651
‐ Rebs!
Coming from the woods!

01:07.651 --> 01:10.445
Rebs!
In the left!

01:10.445 --> 01:13.490
[gunfire]
[all shouting]

01:13.490 --> 01:20.497
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:20.497 --> 01:23.542
[gunfire]

01:23.542 --> 01:26.503
[all shouting]

01:26.503 --> 01:30.007
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:30.007 --> 01:32.009
<i>Rebs!</i>

01:32.009 --> 01:39.099
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:39.808 --> 01:42.769
[horse hooves trotting]

01:42.769 --> 01:48.108
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:48.108 --> 01:51.111
[distant gunfire]

01:51.111 --> 01:58.160
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:06.376 --> 02:11.590
‐ Hurt bad, private?
‐ It's only a scratch, sir.

02:11.590 --> 02:13.050
‐ So you can fight?

02:13.050 --> 02:17.137
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:17.137 --> 02:19.097
Come on now, boys.

02:19.097 --> 02:22.100
Pitch in.
I'm right behind you.

02:22.100 --> 02:26.647
[indistinct shouting]

02:26.647 --> 02:33.654
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:33.654 --> 02:36.657
<i>Everyone has</i>
<i>his superstitions.</i>

02:36.657 --> 02:39.326
<i>One of my superstitions</i>
<i>has always been</i>

02:39.326 --> 02:42.746
<i>when I started to go anywhere</i>
<i>or do anything,</i>

02:42.746 --> 02:44.998
<i>never to turn back or stop</i>

02:44.998 --> 02:49.586
<i>until the thing intended</i>
<i>was accomplished.</i>

02:49.586 --> 02:54.049
‐ General Grant.
‐ Sherman.

02:54.049 --> 02:56.760
‐ We've had the devil's
own day, haven't we?

02:56.760 --> 03:02.182
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:02.182 --> 03:04.434
‐ Lick them tomorrow though.

03:04.434 --> 03:09.481
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:09.481 --> 03:14.611
<i>‐ Very few people really</i>
<i>know who Ulysses S. Grant was.</i>

03:14.611 --> 03:19.032
<i>‐ Today there is this sense</i>
<i>that he's forgotten.</i>

03:19.032 --> 03:22.494
<i>‐ He's been called</i>
<i>so many things over the years.</i>

03:22.494 --> 03:24.996
<i>‐ The greatest general</i>
<i>of his time.</i>

03:24.996 --> 03:27.332
<i>‐ A military genius.</i>

03:27.332 --> 03:29.042
<i>‐ A bloody butcher.</i>

03:29.042 --> 03:31.044
<i>‐ A corrupt President.</i>

03:31.044 --> 03:34.965
<i>‐ A belligerent drunk</i>
<i>who got lucky.</i>

03:34.965 --> 03:37.050
He didn't get lucky.

03:37.050 --> 03:40.220
<i>‐ Ulysses S. Grant is</i>
<i>this perfectly average,</i>

03:40.220 --> 03:44.224
humble individual from a poor,
hardscrabble background...

03:44.224 --> 03:47.394
<i>‐ With a lot of hard times</i>
<i>and failures in his life.</i>

03:47.394 --> 03:49.855
‐ But he's got
this dogged determination

03:49.855 --> 03:52.190
<i>and this bulldog mentality.</i>

03:52.190 --> 03:53.900
‐ This guy comes
from nothing,

03:53.900 --> 03:56.027
<i>rises to the highest ranks</i>
<i>of the Union army.</i>

03:56.027 --> 03:57.487
<i>‐ Form your lines!</i>

03:57.487 --> 03:59.823
<i>‐ Fights bloody,</i>
<i>terrible battles‐‐</i>

03:59.823 --> 04:02.033
<i>‐ With indomitable will‐‐</i>

04:02.033 --> 04:03.577
‐ To save the Union.

04:03.577 --> 04:05.537
<i>‐ To heal his country.</i>

04:05.537 --> 04:09.708
<i>‐ To lead the nation</i>
<i>towards justice for everybody.</i>

04:09.708 --> 04:13.420
<i>‐ He's the unheroic hero</i>
<i>of our greatest national epic,</i>

04:13.420 --> 04:14.796
<i>the American Civil War.</i>

04:14.796 --> 04:17.591
‐ It's truly
an American story,

04:17.591 --> 04:19.801
<i>not only in patriotism</i>
<i>to the nation,</i>

04:19.801 --> 04:24.347
<i>but for the values of who we</i>
<i>are and who we aspire to be.</i>

04:24.347 --> 04:28.351
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:30.771 --> 04:33.774
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

04:33.774 --> 04:35.567
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:35.567 --> 04:39.946
<i>‐ My family is American</i>
<i>and has been for generations.</i>

04:39.946 --> 04:42.866
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:42.866 --> 04:45.702
<i>At the breaking out of the war</i>
<i>of the revolution,</i>

04:45.702 --> 04:49.247
<i>my grandfather went to join</i>
<i>the Continental Army.</i>

04:49.247 --> 04:51.875
<i>He was present</i>
<i>at the Battle of Bunker Hill.</i>

04:51.875 --> 04:54.961
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:54.961 --> 05:00.592
<i>I was born on the 27th</i>
<i>of April, 1822, in Ohio.</i>

05:00.592 --> 05:04.304
<i>While my father carried</i>
<i>on the manufacture of leather,</i>

05:04.304 --> 05:06.556
<i>I detested the trade.</i>

05:06.556 --> 05:10.811
‐ Ulys, get in here.

05:10.811 --> 05:15.315
About that colt, offer $20.
That's what it's worth.

05:15.315 --> 05:20.237
If old Ralston says no,
then you offer 25.

05:20.237 --> 05:22.155
Don't make a mess of it.

05:22.155 --> 05:25.325
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:25.325 --> 05:26.952
<i>‐ There was Mr. Ralston,</i>

05:26.952 --> 05:29.120
<i>living within a few miles</i>
<i>of the village,</i>

05:29.120 --> 05:32.332
<i>who owned a colt</i>
<i>which I very much wanted.</i>

05:32.332 --> 05:33.834
‐ [shushes]

05:33.834 --> 05:36.670
[roosters crowing]

05:36.670 --> 05:38.171
Well?

05:38.171 --> 05:42.300
‐ Pop says I can offer you $20
for the colt,

05:42.300 --> 05:45.929
but if you won't take that,
I can offer you 25.

05:45.929 --> 05:50.141
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:50.141 --> 05:53.019
‐ 25 it is, son.

05:53.019 --> 05:54.646
[boys laughing]

05:54.646 --> 05:58.149
<i>‐ That transaction caused me</i>
<i>much heartburn.</i>

05:58.149 --> 06:00.068
‐ Ulysses.
‐ Ulysses.

06:00.068 --> 06:03.613
More like useless.
Useless Grant.

06:03.613 --> 06:05.198
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:05.198 --> 06:08.493
<i>‐ Grant as a kid showed</i>
<i>no promise for anything.</i>

06:08.493 --> 06:11.204
The local kids called him
Useless Grant

06:11.204 --> 06:13.832
rather than Ulysses Grant.

06:13.832 --> 06:16.877
<i>‐ Grant doesn't have,</i>
<i>probably, the best childhood</i>

06:16.877 --> 06:19.170
in terms
of an overbearing father.

06:19.170 --> 06:20.297
<i>‐ Ulysses really</i>
<i>has nothing</i>

06:20.297 --> 06:22.090
<i>in common with his father.</i>

06:22.090 --> 06:24.175
<i>He does not want to follow</i>
<i>in the family business,</i>

06:24.175 --> 06:26.303
<i>does not like the tannery.</i>

06:26.303 --> 06:27.679
He's repulsed by the smell.

06:27.679 --> 06:29.139
He's repulsed
by the sight of blood.

06:29.139 --> 06:30.432
He just doesn't like it,

06:30.432 --> 06:32.142
but what he does like
is horses.

06:32.142 --> 06:34.978
He becomes an avid horseman
at a very young age,

06:34.978 --> 06:38.565
<i>and that's going to be</i>
<i>very helpful down the road.</i>

06:38.565 --> 06:40.859
<i>‐ I think his father thought,</i>
<i>"What am I gonna do</i>

06:40.859 --> 06:43.194
<i>with Ulysses?"</i>
<i>and so his father is able</i>

06:43.194 --> 06:46.323
<i>to get Grant</i>
<i>an appointment to West Point,</i>

06:46.323 --> 06:48.575
but he'd applied, apparently,
without Grant knowing,

06:48.575 --> 06:50.285
<i>and so when the notice</i>
<i>came of the appointment,</i>

06:50.285 --> 06:52.412
<i>his father says</i>
<i>to Ulysses that,</i>

06:52.412 --> 06:54.122
<i>"You've got the appointment,"</i>

06:54.122 --> 06:56.249
and Grant's response was,
"The appointment to what?"

06:56.249 --> 06:58.376
He goes, "Well, to West Point.
You're going to West Point."

06:58.376 --> 07:00.795
<i>‐ And Grant said,</i>
<i>"I don't really think so,"</i>

07:00.795 --> 07:03.923
and his father says,
"Yes‐‐yes, you are,"

07:03.923 --> 07:05.759
<i>and he ends up going,</i>

07:05.759 --> 07:08.845
but Grant emphatically
did not want to be a soldier.

07:08.845 --> 07:12.515
<i>‐ I would have been glad to</i>
<i>have had a railroad collision</i>

07:12.515 --> 07:15.560
<i>or any other accident happen</i>
<i>by which I might have received</i>

07:15.560 --> 07:17.771
<i>a temporary injury sufficient</i>

07:17.771 --> 07:20.857
<i>to make me ineligible</i>
<i>to enter the academy.</i>

07:20.857 --> 07:24.694
<i>Nothing of the kind occurred,</i>
<i>and I had to face the music.</i>

07:24.694 --> 07:28.990
‐ Sir, there's been a mistake.

07:28.990 --> 07:31.368
See, this says
Ulysses S. Grant.

07:31.368 --> 07:34.037
My name is Ulysses H. Grant.

07:38.458 --> 07:40.585
‐ You've been
officially accepted

07:40.585 --> 07:42.879
as Ulysses S. Grant.

07:42.879 --> 07:44.673
‐ Well, they got that wrong.

07:46.925 --> 07:49.469
‐ This is the name
that's been submitted.

07:49.469 --> 07:53.056
This is the name
you shall have.

07:54.641 --> 07:57.060
‐ Um, yes, sir.

08:00.230 --> 08:01.648
‐ Let me see that.

08:04.567 --> 08:07.737
Ulysses S. Grant.

08:07.737 --> 08:09.989
Longstreet,
this man's name is U. S. Grant.

08:09.989 --> 08:12.575
‐ A fine appellation
if ever there was one.

08:12.575 --> 08:14.411
<i>‐ Uncle Sam Grant.</i>

08:14.411 --> 08:17.247
Well, Sam,
I'm William Tecumseh Sherman.

08:17.247 --> 08:19.249
This here is James Longstreet
of South Carolina.

08:19.249 --> 08:20.417
Call him Pete.

08:20.417 --> 08:21.918
‐ Pleasure, sir.
‐ How do you do?

08:21.918 --> 08:25.296
‐ Welcome to West Point.

08:25.296 --> 08:29.342
<i>‐ The initials U. S. Grant are</i>
<i>actually a complete accident.</i>

08:29.342 --> 08:31.177
<i>When that name appears,</i>

08:31.177 --> 08:33.763
<i>his fellow cadets immediately</i>
<i>start making nicknames.</i>

08:33.763 --> 08:36.015
United States Grant,
Uncle Sam Grant,

08:36.015 --> 08:39.686
and it's Sam
that sticks with him.

08:39.686 --> 08:43.773
‐ If you attended West Point,
you were a very, very prime

08:43.773 --> 08:46.609
specimen in the United States
of America at that point.

08:46.609 --> 08:49.154
<i>‐ Almost all</i>
<i>of the senior generals</i>

08:49.154 --> 08:53.491
of the Civil War on both sides
graduated from West Point.

08:53.491 --> 08:55.326
<i>In the North you had Sherman.</i>

08:55.326 --> 08:59.122
<i>You had McClellan.</i>
<i>You had Sheridan and Meade.</i>

08:59.122 --> 09:01.124
<i>In the South you had</i>
<i>Stonewall Jackson.</i>

09:01.124 --> 09:03.543
<i>You had Longstreet.</i>
<i>You had Jeb Stuart.</i>

09:03.543 --> 09:05.503
<i>You had Robert E. Lee.</i>

09:05.503 --> 09:08.840
<i>Lee was second in his class,</i>
<i>one of the very rare cadets</i>

09:08.840 --> 09:11.301
<i>in history</i>
<i>to have no demerits.</i>

09:11.301 --> 09:13.720
‐ It was very important
at West Point that Grant

09:13.720 --> 09:17.515
met many of the future generals
of the Civil War.

09:17.515 --> 09:20.518
<i>His intimate knowledge</i>
<i>of their personalities</i>

09:20.518 --> 09:22.187
<i>would fill him with confidence</i>

09:22.187 --> 09:27.025
when he found them on the other
side of the battlefield.

09:27.025 --> 09:29.402
<i>‐ He was not a model cadet.</i>

09:29.402 --> 09:30.945
He has plenty of demerits.

09:30.945 --> 09:33.156
<i>‐ He was in the middle</i>
<i>of his class.</i>

09:33.156 --> 09:36.493
As he confessed later on,
he mostly read novels.

09:36.493 --> 09:38.578
<i>‐ But he was good in math.</i>

09:38.578 --> 09:42.999
He enjoyed the art classes.
He enjoyed mapmaking classes.

09:42.999 --> 09:45.668
<i>‐ And he excelled</i>
<i>at horsemanship.</i>

09:45.668 --> 09:49.172
<i>He could tame</i>
<i>seemingly any horse.</i>

09:49.172 --> 09:53.718
<i>‐ Now unfortunately for Grant,</i>
<i>when he graduates,</i>

09:53.718 --> 09:57.597
<i>there were no spots</i>
<i>in the U. S. Cavalry,</i>

09:57.597 --> 09:59.099
and so the best equestrian

09:59.099 --> 10:00.975
in that particular
graduating class

10:00.975 --> 10:02.852
ended up in the infantry.

10:02.852 --> 10:07.690
<i>‐ I reported for duty at</i>
<i>Jefferson barracks, St. Louis.</i>

10:07.690 --> 10:09.734
<i>At West Point</i>
<i>I had a roommate,</i>

10:09.734 --> 10:11.778
<i>Fred Dent,</i>

10:11.778 --> 10:15.740
<i>whose family resided some five</i>
<i>miles west of the barracks.</i>

10:15.740 --> 10:20.245
<i>I soon found my way out to</i>
<i>White Haven, the Dent estate.</i>

10:20.245 --> 10:22.539
<i>As I found</i>
<i>the family congenial,</i>

10:22.539 --> 10:25.166
<i>my visits became frequent.</i>

10:25.166 --> 10:27.335
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

10:27.335 --> 10:30.338
<i>‐ The Dents were</i>
<i>a slave‐owning family.</i>

10:30.338 --> 10:34.008
<i>They had</i>
<i>approximately 30 slaves.</i>

10:34.008 --> 10:37.262
<i>There's no evidence</i>
<i>that Grant felt discomfort</i>

10:37.262 --> 10:40.306
<i>with the Dents' slaves</i>
<i>at that point.</i>

10:40.306 --> 10:44.227
By his own later admission,
he was not an abolitionist.

10:44.227 --> 10:46.646
<i>Marcia: During Grant's time</i>
<i>in Missouri,</i>

10:46.646 --> 10:48.648
<i>the entire nation found itself</i>

10:48.648 --> 10:51.734
<i>divided over the issue</i>
<i>of slavery.</i>

10:51.734 --> 10:55.280
The United States was engaged
in I would say

10:55.280 --> 10:59.617
kind of a fiction that you
could maintain national unity

10:59.617 --> 11:01.828
if you created a balance
of slave and free states.

11:01.828 --> 11:06.624
<i>‐ Enslaved black people were</i>
<i>the largest asset of wealth</i>

11:06.624 --> 11:10.086
<i>that we had in this country,</i>
<i>and so many Americans</i>

11:10.086 --> 11:13.673
<i>wanted to maintain</i>
<i>the right of enslavement,</i>

11:13.673 --> 11:15.425
and when I say enslavement,

11:15.425 --> 11:16.968
I'm talking about for the right
to break up families,

11:16.968 --> 11:18.261
for the right to sell
somebody's mother,

11:18.261 --> 11:19.679
somebody's kid away,

11:19.679 --> 11:21.639
<i>for the right</i>
<i>to torture people.</i>

11:21.639 --> 11:23.766
<i>‐ So the question of slavery</i>

11:23.766 --> 11:25.810
<i>and the atrocities</i>
<i>of the system</i>

11:25.810 --> 11:28.646
was about the direction
that the nation would take

11:28.646 --> 11:31.441
economically but also morally.

11:31.441 --> 11:36.404
‐ Grant's dad, Jesse, is
a huge anti‐slavery advocate.

11:36.404 --> 11:39.240
He's very vocal about
his opinions and his beliefs.

11:39.240 --> 11:41.201
<i>‐ So Grant would have</i>
<i>been well aware</i>

11:41.201 --> 11:44.037
of the long‐simmering
tensions

11:44.037 --> 11:48.833
between slaveholding
and non‐slaveholding states.

11:48.833 --> 11:53.338
<i>At West Point he was friends</i>
<i>with slaveholding men,</i>

11:53.338 --> 11:56.216
<i>many who become</i>
<i>some of his closest friends.</i>

11:56.216 --> 12:00.553
<i>Grant certainly was</i>
<i>part of that tension.</i>

12:00.553 --> 12:03.473
<i>[tense music]</i>

12:03.473 --> 12:05.892
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:05.892 --> 12:08.728
‐ Grant, you haven't yet
met my sister Julia.

12:08.728 --> 12:13.566
Julia, this is Sam,
that is, Ulysses Grant.

12:13.566 --> 12:16.694
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:16.694 --> 12:19.530
‐ You haven't spoken,
Lieutenant Grant.

12:19.530 --> 12:21.407
‐ That's our Grant.

12:21.407 --> 12:23.910
You'll find that he can
be silent in several languages.

12:23.910 --> 12:27.080
<i>‐ Grant, far from looking</i>
<i>for a girlfriend</i>

12:27.080 --> 12:30.166
<i>or looking for a wife</i>
<i>at the time,</i>

12:30.166 --> 12:33.336
was as surprised as anyone
that he had fallen in love.

12:33.336 --> 12:35.588
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:35.588 --> 12:39.175
‐ However, Julia Dent is
the daughter of a slave owner.

12:39.175 --> 12:41.719
<i>It's gonna create</i>
<i>some dilemmas for Grant.</i>

12:41.719 --> 12:43.513
<i>It's gonna cause</i>
<i>a lot of friction</i>

12:43.513 --> 12:45.932
because Jesse Grant,
anti‐slavery.

12:45.932 --> 12:47.558
Frederick Dent,
slave owner.

12:47.558 --> 12:49.936
<i>The families</i>
<i>are very much opposed.</i>

12:49.936 --> 12:54.565
<i>‐ So Grant has a secret</i>
<i>engagement with Julia,</i>

12:54.565 --> 12:56.776
<i>and they were going</i>
<i>to approach</i>

12:56.776 --> 12:58.236
<i>Colonel Dent about it,</i>

12:58.236 --> 13:00.780
<i>but it's put on hold</i>
<i>indefinitely</i>

13:00.780 --> 13:03.533
as he's called
to the Mexican‐American War.

13:03.533 --> 13:06.786
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:06.786 --> 13:09.414
<i>‐ The thing that led</i>
<i>to the Mexican War</i>

13:09.414 --> 13:12.458
was the westward expansion
of the United States

13:12.458 --> 13:14.877
<i>into Mexican territory</i>

13:14.877 --> 13:17.672
<i>with an incredibly</i>
<i>aggressive foreign policy</i>

13:17.672 --> 13:20.717
<i>to unify the country</i>
<i>all the way to California,</i>

13:20.717 --> 13:23.970
<i>which was the crown jewel</i>
<i>on the west coast.</i>

13:23.970 --> 13:28.641
<i>Mexico stood in the way,</i>
<i>so the army marches in.</i>

13:28.641 --> 13:31.602
<i>Ulysses S. Grant is assigned</i>
<i>as a quartermaster‐‐</i>

13:31.602 --> 13:33.813
<i>that is, a supply officer.</i>

13:33.813 --> 13:36.774
<i>Grant is a spectacular</i>
<i>quartermaster,</i>

13:36.774 --> 13:38.735
<i>incredibly hands‐on,</i>

13:38.735 --> 13:42.447
<i>but he is itching</i>
<i>to get into combat.</i>

13:42.447 --> 13:45.658
<i>He is a 25‐year‐old</i>
<i>West Point graduate</i>

13:45.658 --> 13:49.454
who has an opportunity
to make a name for himself.

13:49.454 --> 13:52.331
[gunfire]

13:52.331 --> 13:55.585
<i>[tense music]</i>

13:55.585 --> 13:58.838
[all shouting at once]

13:58.838 --> 14:01.007
[gunfire]

14:01.007 --> 14:02.759
<i>‐ To Colonel Garland,</i>

14:02.759 --> 14:05.178
<i>I respectfully protest</i>
<i>against being assigned</i>

14:05.178 --> 14:06.512
<i>the duties of quartermaster...</i>

14:06.512 --> 14:08.306
Boys, load those boxes.

14:08.306 --> 14:10.183
<i>Which removes me</i>
<i>from sharing in the dangers</i>

14:10.183 --> 14:14.103
<i>and honors of service</i>
<i>with my company at the front.</i>

14:14.103 --> 14:18.357
‐ I need ammunition!
‐ Yes, sir!

14:18.357 --> 14:21.402
‐ Come on, guys, mount!
Rush in!

14:21.402 --> 14:24.614
[all shouting]
[gunfire]

14:24.614 --> 14:27.784
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:27.784 --> 14:29.160
[shouting]

14:29.160 --> 14:32.455
‐ Ammunition!
Ammunition!

14:32.455 --> 14:34.207
<i>Ammo, now!</i>

14:34.207 --> 14:38.044
‐ Volunteer!
Volunteer!

14:38.044 --> 14:39.879
[booming]

14:39.879 --> 14:41.172
‐ I volunteer.

14:41.172 --> 14:42.882
‐ Grant, you're
the quartermaster.

14:42.882 --> 14:44.884
You don't need to do this.
‐ You asked for a volunteer.

14:44.884 --> 14:46.052
‐ I need ammunition!
Come on!

14:46.052 --> 14:48.304
‐ I volunteer.

14:48.304 --> 14:49.722
‐ We're gonna lose
this position

14:49.722 --> 14:52.016
unless we get ammunition
up here now.

14:52.016 --> 14:56.020
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:56.020 --> 14:58.564
[gunfire]

15:00.608 --> 15:02.235
[all shouting]
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:02.235 --> 15:09.242
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:13.162 --> 15:15.081
‐ God save you, Grant!

15:15.081 --> 15:18.709
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:18.709 --> 15:20.169
<i>‐ In the Mexican War,</i>

15:20.169 --> 15:21.879
<i>there's a very</i>
<i>dramatic incident</i>

15:21.879 --> 15:24.590
<i>where Grant rides</i>
<i>on the side of a horse</i>

15:24.590 --> 15:26.175
<i>using the horse as a shield</i>

15:26.175 --> 15:28.594
<i>as he rides</i>
<i>a gauntlet of bullets</i>

15:28.594 --> 15:31.931
to keep these men supplied
in the middle of a battle.

15:31.931 --> 15:35.768
<i>‐ In the Mexican War Grant</i>
<i>learns a very important lesson</i>

15:35.768 --> 15:38.813
<i>about his own</i>
<i>emotional makeup.</i>

15:38.813 --> 15:40.189
In moments of extreme danger,

15:40.189 --> 15:42.859
when other people
are panicking,

15:42.859 --> 15:46.612
<i>Grant becomes very cool</i>
<i>in a crisis.</i>

15:46.612 --> 15:51.617
<i>He discovers nothing ever</i>
<i>rattled him in battle.</i>

15:51.617 --> 15:53.286
<i>‐ You want to know</i>

15:53.286 --> 15:55.955
<i>what my feelings</i>
<i>were on the field of battle?</i>

15:55.955 --> 16:00.418
<i>I do not know that I felt</i>
<i>any peculiar sensation.</i>

16:00.418 --> 16:04.672
<i>War seems much less horrible</i>
<i>to persons engaged in it</i>

16:04.672 --> 16:07.258
<i>than to those</i>
<i>who read of the battle.</i>

16:07.258 --> 16:09.552
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:09.552 --> 16:13.181
<i>‐ Grant watches people die</i>
<i>horrible deaths in battle.</i>

16:13.181 --> 16:16.851
<i>He loses many of his friends,</i>
<i>one after the other,</i>

16:16.851 --> 16:19.020
and so I think
he has a very clear sense

16:19.020 --> 16:22.523
of the costs of war
from the start.

16:22.523 --> 16:24.901
<i>‐ Many West Point‐trained</i>
<i>officers</i>

16:24.901 --> 16:27.945
<i>served together during</i>
<i>the U. S. war with Mexico.</i>

16:27.945 --> 16:30.406
<i>That's where Grant met</i>
<i>Robert E. Lee</i>

16:30.406 --> 16:34.160
for the first time,
Grant as a lower‐level officer

16:34.160 --> 16:37.872
but Lee as a major
staff officer.

16:37.872 --> 16:40.625
<i>Lee is a hero during the war.</i>

16:40.625 --> 16:43.336
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:43.336 --> 16:47.715
<i>‐ The Mexican War ends</i>
<i>in 1848.</i>

16:47.715 --> 16:50.968
We have gotten exactly
what we want,

16:50.968 --> 16:54.180
<i>most of the American</i>
<i>Southwest,</i>

16:54.180 --> 16:57.183
<i>roughly 500,000 square miles</i>
<i>of territory,</i>

16:57.183 --> 16:59.602
<i>all the way</i>
<i>to the Pacific Ocean,</i>

16:59.602 --> 17:01.938
<i>and the question of whether</i>
<i>that land would be</i>

17:01.938 --> 17:03.606
<i>slave or free,</i>
<i>of course,</i>

17:03.606 --> 17:06.859
would raise its ugly head
pretty much every year

17:06.859 --> 17:10.029
after that right up to 1861.

17:10.029 --> 17:14.367
<i>In many ways, the completion</i>
<i>of the United States</i>

17:14.367 --> 17:17.703
<i>from sea to shining sea</i>
<i>leads directly</i>

17:17.703 --> 17:19.538
<i>to the American Civil War.</i>

17:19.538 --> 17:26.212
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:26.212 --> 17:29.215
[horse whinnying]

17:32.134 --> 17:35.054
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

17:35.054 --> 17:37.056
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:37.056 --> 17:40.268
<i>‐ By the time Grant came</i>
<i>back from the Mexican War,</i>

17:40.268 --> 17:45.231
<i>he had matured,</i>
<i>and Julia was waiting for him,</i>

17:45.231 --> 17:47.900
<i>but Julia's father,</i>
<i>Colonel Dent,</i>

17:47.900 --> 17:49.277
thought she could do better.

17:49.277 --> 17:51.404
<i>He thought that</i>
<i>the military life</i>

17:51.404 --> 17:54.323
<i>would be</i>
<i>very difficult for her.</i>

17:54.323 --> 17:56.909
‐ Grant eventually won
over Dent

17:56.909 --> 17:59.579
<i>and asked to marry Julia.</i>

17:59.579 --> 18:02.540
‐ But Grant came from
a strongly abolitionist family

18:02.540 --> 18:05.918
that was horrified
that he was marrying into

18:05.918 --> 18:08.462
this Missouri
slave‐owning family,

18:08.462 --> 18:12.300
<i>and when Ulysses and Julia</i>
<i>get married in 1848,</i>

18:12.300 --> 18:16.637
<i>not a single member</i>
<i>of the Grant family is there.</i>

18:16.637 --> 18:21.100
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:21.100 --> 18:22.810
<i>‐ The first years</i>

18:22.810 --> 18:25.271
<i>of that marriage</i>
<i>are actually quite difficult.</i>

18:25.271 --> 18:29.108
<i>Grant is posted to the</i>
<i>west coast, to Fort Humboldt.</i>

18:29.108 --> 18:32.320
Julia is expecting a child
and is thus unable

18:32.320 --> 18:35.239
to go with him
to the Pacific Northwest.

18:35.239 --> 18:36.782
<i>‐ When he was separated</i>
<i>from his family,</i>

18:36.782 --> 18:40.411
<i>he missed them terribly,</i>
<i>especially Julia,</i>

18:40.411 --> 18:42.455
and Fort Humboldt
was an isolated,

18:42.455 --> 18:44.624
desolate place to be,

18:44.624 --> 18:48.919
<i>so he really started to suffer</i>
<i>significant melancholy.</i>

18:48.919 --> 18:55.968
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:55.968 --> 18:58.179
<i>‐ Dear Julia, the mail came</i>

18:58.179 --> 19:00.056
<i>but brought me nothing</i>
<i>from you.</i>

19:00.056 --> 19:02.642
<i>I have only had one letter</i>
<i>from you in three months.</i>

19:02.642 --> 19:06.312
<i>My dear wife, how very anxious</i>
<i>I am to get home once again.</i>

19:06.312 --> 19:08.272
<i>I sometimes get so anxious</i>

19:08.272 --> 19:09.857
<i>to see you</i>
<i>and our little boys,</i>

19:09.857 --> 19:11.651
<i>I'm almost tempted to resign.</i>

19:11.651 --> 19:13.653
<i>Dear Julia,</i>
<i>I do not feel</i>

19:13.653 --> 19:18.157
<i>as if it is possible to endure</i>
<i>this separation much longer.</i>

19:18.157 --> 19:25.164
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:25.164 --> 19:29.627
<i>‐ Grant gets bored easily</i>
<i>when there's nothing going on.</i>

19:29.627 --> 19:34.090
He gets lonely, and that
is when you start seeing

19:34.090 --> 19:38.177
maybe some problems
with the drinking.

19:38.177 --> 19:40.221
‐ Thank you, sir.

19:40.221 --> 19:43.224
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:43.224 --> 19:45.101
<i>‐ When I have nothing to do,</i>

19:45.101 --> 19:47.061
<i>I get blue,</i>

19:47.061 --> 19:50.690
<i>and I have</i>
<i>a natural craving for a drink.</i>

19:50.690 --> 19:52.942
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:52.942 --> 19:55.277
‐ Captain Grant.

20:04.286 --> 20:09.291
Grant, you know
the rules about drink.

20:17.717 --> 20:19.385
<i>‐ This is where</i>
<i>all the stories</i>

20:19.385 --> 20:21.846
<i>of Grant's drinking start.</i>

20:21.846 --> 20:25.725
<i>I think there were some times</i>
<i>when he did drink.</i>

20:25.725 --> 20:28.936
<i>It was a story that circulated</i>
<i>among army officers,</i>

20:28.936 --> 20:33.357
and then later it became
an easy thing

20:33.357 --> 20:37.361
for those who vilified him
or wished to to seize on.

20:37.361 --> 20:40.906
<i>It became one of the running</i>
<i>themes of his life.</i>

20:40.906 --> 20:42.783
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:42.783 --> 20:46.579
‐ Grant, I'm sorry
it's come to this.

20:48.539 --> 20:50.291
You have a choice:

20:50.291 --> 20:54.754
resign or court martial.

20:54.754 --> 21:01.844
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:04.972 --> 21:08.851
<i>[country music]</i>

21:08.851 --> 21:11.353
[horse braying]

21:11.353 --> 21:15.274
[donkey hawing]

21:15.274 --> 21:18.652
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:18.652 --> 21:22.281
‐ Hey, mister,
you a soldier?

21:22.281 --> 21:25.117
‐ Uh, n‐no, I'm‐‐

21:25.117 --> 21:28.954
‐ Then why are you wearing
that old soldier's coat?

21:28.954 --> 21:33.709
‐ It's a good coat,
but I'm not a soldier anymore.

21:33.709 --> 21:35.544
‐ So what are you?

21:35.544 --> 21:42.593
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:45.971 --> 21:49.391
‐ May I ask who you are?

21:49.391 --> 21:53.312
‐ Grant, Fred Grant.

21:53.312 --> 21:55.231
‐ Ulys!

21:55.231 --> 21:58.651
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:58.651 --> 22:00.152
Ulys!

22:00.152 --> 22:03.989
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:03.989 --> 22:08.911
[laughing]

22:08.911 --> 22:11.580
<i>‐ When Grant arrives back</i>
<i>at White Haven,</i>

22:11.580 --> 22:14.333
<i>it must have been an</i>
<i>absolutely surreal experience.</i>

22:14.333 --> 22:18.754
<i>He hadn't seen his wife,</i>
<i>Julia, in two years.</i>

22:18.754 --> 22:23.676
<i>He hadn't seen his young son,</i>
<i>Fred, in two years,</i>

22:23.676 --> 22:25.886
and he had never even met
his youngest son,

22:25.886 --> 22:29.431
Ulysses Jr.‐‐
his namesake.

22:29.431 --> 22:31.517
<i>‐ Grant is now very much</i>

22:31.517 --> 22:33.227
<i>lorded over by</i>
<i>his father‐in‐law,</i>

22:33.227 --> 22:36.188
Colonel Dent,
who is convinced

22:36.188 --> 22:39.859
that his daughter
has married beneath her.

22:39.859 --> 22:44.864
<i>So there's a slow burn</i>
<i>going on in Ulysses Grant.</i>

22:44.864 --> 22:46.907
<i>‐ Grant wants</i>
<i>to be independent.</i>

22:46.907 --> 22:48.868
<i>He wants to get out</i>
<i>of the main house,</i>

22:48.868 --> 22:53.873
<i>to get away from Colonel Dent,</i>
<i>and so he builds Hardscrabble</i>

22:53.873 --> 22:57.376
<i>on the 60 acres given</i>
<i>by Colonel Dent to Julia.</i>

22:57.376 --> 23:00.379
<i>He's got to clear the land,</i>
<i>clear the wood.</i>

23:00.379 --> 23:03.340
<i>He wants to have his family</i>
<i>in their own home.</i>

23:03.340 --> 23:07.344
<i>That is the independent</i>
<i>streak in him.</i>

23:07.344 --> 23:11.140
[wood splitting]

23:11.140 --> 23:14.685
<i>Julia had absolute trust</i>
<i>in her husband.</i>

23:14.685 --> 23:18.355
<i>He wasn't looking</i>
<i>for fame, fortune.</i>

23:18.355 --> 23:21.901
<i>His ambitions centered</i>
<i>on his family.</i>

23:21.901 --> 23:24.236
<i>He would say,</i>
<i>"You know my weaknesses,</i>

23:24.236 --> 23:26.196
<i>my horses and my children."</i>

23:26.196 --> 23:30.409
‐ [groans]
‐ [laughs]

23:30.409 --> 23:32.786
<i>‐ Grant is now faced</i>

23:32.786 --> 23:34.955
<i>with the challenge</i>
<i>of making a living.</i>

23:34.955 --> 23:37.416
He tried farming.
That doesn't work out so well.

23:37.416 --> 23:40.836
<i>He tries a real estate</i>
<i>business in St. Louis,</i>

23:40.836 --> 23:43.756
<i>but he's not really very good</i>
<i>at collecting rent.</i>

23:43.756 --> 23:46.091
<i>He tries to get a job</i>
<i>as a surveyor,</i>

23:46.091 --> 23:47.760
and he isn't able to get that.

23:47.760 --> 23:50.429
<i>He doesn't really know</i>
<i>what to do.</i>

23:50.429 --> 23:53.933
<i>What's staring him</i>
<i>in the face is poverty.</i>

23:53.933 --> 23:58.270
<i>‐ I did not want to fly</i>
<i>from one thing to another,</i>

23:58.270 --> 24:02.691
<i>but I was compelled to make</i>
<i>a living for my family.</i>

24:02.691 --> 24:05.778
<i>If nothing else could be done,</i>
<i>I would load a cord of wood</i>

24:05.778 --> 24:08.447
<i>and take it to the city</i>
<i>for sale.</i>

24:08.447 --> 24:13.327
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:14.203 --> 24:16.163
[horse brays]

24:16.163 --> 24:18.666
‐ Captain Grant?
‐ Whoa, whoa.

24:21.961 --> 24:25.673
‐ I served under you in Mexico,
Molino del Rey.

24:25.673 --> 24:27.132
‐ Oh.

24:27.132 --> 24:30.886
‐ Hell of a day, sir.
‐ Yes.

24:32.137 --> 24:34.223
‐ May I ask
what you're doing, sir?

24:36.141 --> 24:38.477
‐ Solving the problem
of poverty.

24:42.856 --> 24:44.733
‐ Sir.

24:47.695 --> 24:51.907
<i>‐ Many people think that</i>
<i>Grant selling firewood</i>

24:51.907 --> 24:53.701
<i>was beneath him,</i>

24:53.701 --> 24:57.037
but the reality was he was
willing to do whatever it took

24:57.037 --> 24:59.164
to provide for his family.

24:59.164 --> 25:02.710
I think that's the core
of Ulysses S. Grant.

25:02.710 --> 25:04.837
<i>You will encounter hardships.</i>

25:04.837 --> 25:07.506
<i>You will encounter failures,</i>

25:07.506 --> 25:09.049
<i>but you've got</i>
<i>to keep pushing.</i>

25:09.049 --> 25:11.552
<i>You've gotta keep persevering.</i>

25:11.552 --> 25:14.179
<i>[tense music]</i>

25:14.179 --> 25:16.390
<i>‐ He also, however,</i>
<i>was living</i>

25:16.390 --> 25:18.934
<i>in a kind</i>
<i>of divided household.</i>

25:18.934 --> 25:21.186
<i>He's living with</i>
<i>the Dent slaves,</i>

25:21.186 --> 25:24.356
and Grant grew up in a home
where his own father

25:24.356 --> 25:27.693
was very vocal
in his anti‐slavery attitudes.

25:27.693 --> 25:31.196
<i>He is not an abolitionist.</i>

25:31.196 --> 25:34.116
<i>In fact, Grant acquires</i>
<i>from Colonel Dent</i>

25:34.116 --> 25:35.909
<i>a slave,</i>
<i>William Jones,</i>

25:35.909 --> 25:38.871
<i>but he's criticized</i>
<i>by the Dents</i>

25:38.871 --> 25:40.372
<i>and by their neighbors</i>

25:40.372 --> 25:43.375
for working alongside
the slaves in the fields.

25:43.375 --> 25:47.046
<i>‐ He actually got ridiculed</i>
<i>by some of his neighbors</i>

25:47.046 --> 25:49.840
for being too nice
to his wife's slaves,

25:49.840 --> 25:52.217
<i>that he was not</i>
<i>whipping them enough.</i>

25:52.217 --> 25:54.553
<i>‐ I don't know why</i>
<i>a black skin</i>

25:54.553 --> 25:59.391
<i>may not cover a true heart</i>
<i>as well as a white one.</i>

25:59.391 --> 26:02.895
‐ In the late 1850s,
Grant obviously

26:02.895 --> 26:07.441
was already wrestling
with this slavery issue.

26:07.441 --> 26:11.445
<i>‐ And then this new</i>
<i>political party surfaces,</i>

26:11.445 --> 26:13.614
<i>the Republicans,</i>

26:13.614 --> 26:16.241
<i>and they have</i>
<i>as their platform</i>

26:16.241 --> 26:18.494
not the abolition of slavery

26:18.494 --> 26:20.662
but to stop slavery
from spreading

26:20.662 --> 26:23.373
<i>to new territories</i>
<i>of the United States.</i>

26:23.373 --> 26:25.959
<i>‐ Slaveholders</i>
<i>don't see it that way,</i>

26:25.959 --> 26:29.588
and they believe that all
Republicans want to end slavery

26:29.588 --> 26:31.590
even in the slaveholding South.

26:31.590 --> 26:36.845
<i>Neither side is happy,</i>
<i>and things start amping up.</i>

26:36.845 --> 26:40.015
‐ Grant found himself caught
in the crossfire

26:40.015 --> 26:44.103
between the abolitionist Grants
and the slave‐owning Dents,

26:44.103 --> 26:46.814
<i>but he had enough reservations</i>
<i>about slavery</i>

26:46.814 --> 26:48.732
<i>that in March 1859</i>

26:48.732 --> 26:52.111
<i>Grant goes to the circuit</i>
<i>court in St. Louis.</i>

26:52.111 --> 26:58.408
‐ Name, age?
‐ Jones, William, 34.

27:01.203 --> 27:02.955
‐ Prices are up.

27:02.955 --> 27:06.291
I've got a friend
that'll get you $1,000 for him.

27:06.291 --> 27:07.543
Are you sure you want
to let him free

27:07.543 --> 27:09.336
when you can make some money?

27:09.336 --> 27:10.796
‐ Yes.

27:19.513 --> 27:22.474
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:22.474 --> 27:29.565
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:42.703 --> 27:44.496
God protect you, William.

27:44.496 --> 27:47.666
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:47.666 --> 27:50.168
‐ You also, sir.

27:50.168 --> 27:56.717
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:56.717 --> 28:00.012
<i>‐ Grant sets him free.</i>

28:00.012 --> 28:04.016
When you imagine Grant
restoring freedom

28:04.016 --> 28:05.851
to an enslaved human,

28:05.851 --> 28:08.520
you have to imagine, like,
walking away from your house.

28:08.520 --> 28:10.397
I hate to be
that callous about it,

28:10.397 --> 28:11.940
<i>but you have to imagine</i>
<i>walking away</i>

28:11.940 --> 28:13.775
<i>from the greatest asset</i>

28:13.775 --> 28:17.029
<i>you could possibly have</i>
<i>at a time when you're poor.</i>

28:17.029 --> 28:18.655
You're not gonna
sell the house.

28:18.655 --> 28:20.532
You're gonna walk
away from it.

28:20.532 --> 28:22.784
Uh, it's a tremendous act
of courage.

28:22.784 --> 28:28.248
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:28.248 --> 28:31.793
<i>‐ So finally in 1860, one year</i>
<i>before the Civil War,</i>

28:31.793 --> 28:35.923
Grant, in what must have felt
like the ultimate humiliation,

28:35.923 --> 28:40.260
goes to his overbearing father
and begs his father for a job

28:40.260 --> 28:42.846
<i>as a clerk in his father's</i>
<i>leather goods store</i>

28:42.846 --> 28:46.058
<i>in Bologna, Illinois.</i>

28:46.058 --> 28:48.644
<i>He is bored and restless.</i>

28:48.644 --> 28:54.691
<i>He seems destined for a life</i>
<i>of complete obscurity.</i>

28:54.691 --> 28:58.070
‐ During that time
there's an idealistic visionary

28:58.070 --> 29:01.740
from the west
beginning to emerge

29:01.740 --> 29:04.743
<i>with a special kind</i>
<i>of speaking ability,</i>

29:04.743 --> 29:07.955
<i>who could translate</i>
<i>a sort of folksy,</i>

29:07.955 --> 29:11.249
<i>homespun understanding</i>
<i>of American affairs</i>

29:11.249 --> 29:13.418
<i>to the wider public,</i>

29:13.418 --> 29:15.504
<i>and he becomes</i>
<i>the Republican Party's</i>

29:15.504 --> 29:18.799
<i>standard bearer</i>
<i>in the election of 1860,</i>

29:18.799 --> 29:20.926
<i>and that man</i>
<i>was Abraham Lincoln.</i>

29:20.926 --> 29:24.179
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:24.179 --> 29:27.474
<i>‐ I wanted to see</i>
<i>Mr. Lincoln elected.</i>

29:27.474 --> 29:29.267
<i>Excitement ran high,</i>

29:29.267 --> 29:34.272
<i>and torch‐led processions</i>
<i>enlivened the street.</i>

29:34.272 --> 29:38.068
<i>‐ As the secession</i>
<i>movement gained traction,</i>

29:38.068 --> 29:40.487
<i>Grant was like</i>
<i>many northerners</i>

29:40.487 --> 29:42.948
<i>and a sizeable number</i>
<i>of southerners</i>

29:42.948 --> 29:46.284
who wondered what we could do
to keep the Union together.

29:46.284 --> 29:48.662
He didn't want the Union
to break up.

29:48.662 --> 29:50.539
He thought that
would be a disaster.

29:50.539 --> 29:54.501
<i>‐ I still had hopes for the</i>
<i>extreme pro‐slavery sentiment</i>

29:54.501 --> 29:56.795
<i>to cool down,</i>

29:56.795 --> 29:59.798
<i>but I was mistaken.</i>

29:59.798 --> 30:03.176
<i>‐ The election</i>
<i>of Abraham Lincoln in 1860</i>

30:03.176 --> 30:08.682
is a direct‐‐
direct assault on the South.

30:08.682 --> 30:12.144
<i>The South is feeling</i>
<i>completely under attack,</i>

30:12.144 --> 30:14.646
<i>that the new government</i>
<i>is going to come in,</i>

30:14.646 --> 30:17.315
<i>and they're gonna take away</i>
<i>all their slaves,</i>

30:17.315 --> 30:19.985
<i>and we're not gonna be</i>
<i>a part of a country</i>

30:19.985 --> 30:23.030
that isn't going to help
preserve our way of life.

30:23.030 --> 30:25.699
<i>Now we've gone and elected</i>
<i>this guy</i>

30:25.699 --> 30:28.243
<i>from out</i>
<i>in the middle of Illinois,</i>

30:28.243 --> 30:31.496
this little know‐nothing
lawyer...

30:31.496 --> 30:35.167
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:35.167 --> 30:37.669
And it's on.

30:37.669 --> 30:39.880
<i>‐ A few days after</i>
<i>Lincoln's election,</i>

30:39.880 --> 30:43.341
<i>South Caroline calls</i>
<i>for a secession convention,</i>

30:43.341 --> 30:45.177
and on December the 20th, 1860,

30:45.177 --> 30:49.473
<i>they pull themselves</i>
<i>out of the Union.</i>

30:49.473 --> 30:51.683
<i>Mississippi and Florida</i>
<i>are the second</i>

30:51.683 --> 30:54.019
<i>and third states to follow.</i>

30:54.019 --> 30:58.023
<i>By February 1861,</i>
<i>seven deep Southern states</i>

30:58.023 --> 31:01.610
<i>have left the union to form</i>
<i>the Confederate States.</i>

31:01.610 --> 31:05.447
<i>Four additional states</i>
<i>will leave after the firing</i>

31:05.447 --> 31:07.282
<i>on Fort Sumter.</i>

31:07.282 --> 31:09.701
<i>‐ When Southern coastal</i>
<i>states seceded,</i>

31:09.701 --> 31:12.204
they considered all
of the forts property

31:12.204 --> 31:13.497
of the Confederacy.

31:13.497 --> 31:14.706
Obviously
the federal government

31:14.706 --> 31:15.957
didn't see it that way,

31:15.957 --> 31:17.709
and Lincoln said
he would possess,

31:17.709 --> 31:19.795
hold, and occupy
federal property.

31:19.795 --> 31:22.672
<i>The Confederates wanted</i>
<i>the Union soldiers to leave.</i>

31:22.672 --> 31:26.301
They would not, and the South
opened fire to bombard

31:26.301 --> 31:28.053
Fort Sumter into submission.

31:28.053 --> 31:31.098
<i>[explosions]</i>

31:31.098 --> 31:33.266
<i>‐ The war breaks out,</i>

31:33.266 --> 31:36.561
<i>and the United States</i>
<i>government is desperate</i>

31:36.561 --> 31:38.897
for anyone who's had any kind
of military experience.

31:38.897 --> 31:42.067
<i>‐ Lincoln calls for</i>
<i>75,000 volunteers</i>

31:42.067 --> 31:44.402
<i>to suppress the rebellion.</i>

31:44.402 --> 31:45.904
<i>‐ Most people in the North</i>

31:45.904 --> 31:47.614
thought this would be
a short event.

31:47.614 --> 31:50.117
<i>The Union would</i>
<i>win this war quickly</i>

31:50.117 --> 31:51.451
<i>with its military might,</i>

31:51.451 --> 31:53.954
<i>with its railroads,</i>
<i>with its brave soldiers.</i>

31:53.954 --> 31:57.082
‐ Back in Galena, Illinois,
Grant has a friend,

31:57.082 --> 31:59.751
<i>John Rawlins,</i>
<i>who has received a commission</i>

31:59.751 --> 32:03.588
<i>from the governor</i>
<i>to organize a regiment.</i>

32:04.422 --> 32:08.093
[door closes]

32:08.093 --> 32:10.262
‐ It's damn suicide,
don't you think?

32:10.262 --> 32:12.264
‐ I'd give them 90 days,

32:12.264 --> 32:14.391
but then again,
the South can claim

32:14.391 --> 32:17.602
more than half the officers
at West Point,

32:17.602 --> 32:19.146
and I've seen them in Mexico.

32:19.146 --> 32:21.857
Quick on counterattacks,

32:21.857 --> 32:24.317
know the terrain.

32:24.317 --> 32:26.194
Can't underestimate them.

32:26.194 --> 32:28.155
<i>[tense music]</i>

32:28.155 --> 32:30.490
‐ I'm speaking at
the courthouse later,

32:30.490 --> 32:32.659
hoping to raise
a regiment here.

32:32.659 --> 32:34.494
I'm sure the young men
would respect a soldier

32:34.494 --> 32:37.497
with your experience.
‐ Mm.

32:37.497 --> 32:39.166
I'm no speaker.

32:39.166 --> 32:40.458
‐ Oh, hell,

32:40.458 --> 32:42.794
I'm not asking you to speak.

32:42.794 --> 32:46.214
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:46.214 --> 32:48.550
I'm asking you to lead.

32:48.550 --> 32:52.137
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:52.137 --> 32:54.306
[door opens and shuts]

32:54.306 --> 33:01.313
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:04.691 --> 33:08.069
[distant shouting]

33:08.069 --> 33:11.156
<i>‐ The call of the</i>
<i>President for 75,000 men</i>

33:11.156 --> 33:13.825
<i>was heard throughout</i>
<i>the northern states.</i>

33:13.825 --> 33:16.828
<i>[tense music]</i>

33:16.828 --> 33:18.330
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:18.330 --> 33:20.916
<i>There were</i>
<i>but two parties now,</i>

33:20.916 --> 33:23.877
<i>traitors and patriots.</i>

33:23.877 --> 33:25.837
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:25.837 --> 33:29.132
<i>‐ We don't see a lot</i>
<i>of expressions of emotion</i>

33:29.132 --> 33:33.094
<i>from Grant until we talk</i>
<i>about the South seceding,</i>

33:33.094 --> 33:35.430
rebelling against
the United States of America.

33:35.430 --> 33:39.935
This‐‐this grinds
at Ulysses S. Grant.

33:39.935 --> 33:41.770
<i>He grows up listening</i>
<i>about his relatives</i>

33:41.770 --> 33:43.772
<i>fighting in the revolution,</i>

33:43.772 --> 33:46.858
and so he is very emotional
about this idea of traitors.

33:46.858 --> 33:50.111
<i>‐ Dear Father,</i>
<i>my inclination is to whip</i>

33:50.111 --> 33:52.113
<i>the rebellion into submission.</i>

33:52.113 --> 33:54.074
<i>‐ When Jefferson Davis</i>
<i>is sworn in</i>

33:54.074 --> 33:55.992
<i>as Confederate president,</i>

33:55.992 --> 34:00.580
Grant is so upset by it that
he shakes his fist in the air

34:00.580 --> 34:05.877
and says, "Davis and the whole
gang of them ought to be hung."

34:05.877 --> 34:07.587
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:07.587 --> 34:09.256
<i>‐ Many people</i>
<i>in the United States</i>

34:09.256 --> 34:10.966
thought that this experiment

34:10.966 --> 34:13.343
that the founding fathers
had put in place

34:13.343 --> 34:15.679
<i>was in fact still</i>
<i>an experiment</i>

34:15.679 --> 34:17.639
<i>and was in jeopardy,</i>

34:17.639 --> 34:20.642
<i>and this notion of fighting</i>
<i>for the Union was tied up</i>

34:20.642 --> 34:24.521
<i>in believing that what</i>
<i>the founders had created</i>

34:24.521 --> 34:28.566
<i>was in fact worth fighting for</i>
<i>and worth saving,</i>

34:28.566 --> 34:31.027
<i>and that's why so many men</i>
<i>were willing</i>

34:31.027 --> 34:35.991
<i>to risk their lives</i>
<i>to fight for the Union.</i>

34:35.991 --> 34:37.450
<i>‐ Beginning of the war,</i>

34:37.450 --> 34:39.703
<i>we have about</i>
<i>31 million people</i>

34:39.703 --> 34:41.162
<i>in the United States.</i>

34:41.162 --> 34:43.832
<i>About 21 million</i>
<i>live in the North.</i>

34:43.832 --> 34:46.167
<i>About 10 million of them</i>
<i>live in the South,</i>

34:46.167 --> 34:49.337
<i>but in the South about four</i>
<i>million of them are slaves,</i>

34:49.337 --> 34:54.384
<i>so it's really 6 million</i>
<i>against 21 million.</i>

34:54.384 --> 34:57.804
<i>The South is 80% agricultural,</i>
<i>but what do they grow?</i>

34:57.804 --> 35:01.558
Tobacco, cotton,
indigo, rice, corn.

35:01.558 --> 35:03.893
Well, you can only eat
two of those.

35:03.893 --> 35:07.981
<i>From people to manufacturing</i>
<i>to technology,</i>

35:07.981 --> 35:11.693
<i>the North has all</i>
<i>the advantages over the South,</i>

35:11.693 --> 35:13.820
but that doesn't make it
a foregone conclusion

35:13.820 --> 35:15.280
about who will win

35:15.280 --> 35:17.699
because ultimately,
war is a clash of wills,

35:17.699 --> 35:19.659
<i>and in this clash of wills,</i>

35:19.659 --> 35:22.662
<i>maybe, just maybe</i>
<i>the South would win.</i>

35:22.662 --> 35:26.333
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:26.333 --> 35:27.751
<i>‐ After southern secession,</i>

35:27.751 --> 35:29.377
<i>the federal government</i>

35:29.377 --> 35:32.380
<i>was looking for a commander,</i>

35:32.380 --> 35:34.341
this new Union army

35:34.341 --> 35:37.719
that was going to try
to restore the republic.

35:37.719 --> 35:39.471
<i>The first name</i>
<i>that comes to mind</i>

35:39.471 --> 35:43.016
<i>is Robert E. Lee,</i>
<i>a Virginian.</i>

35:43.016 --> 35:45.810
‐ Lee was offered
the command of the Union army

35:45.810 --> 35:47.771
<i>and, of course,</i>
<i>did some deep thinking</i>

35:47.771 --> 35:49.731
<i>and then decided</i>
<i>that his allegiance</i>

35:49.731 --> 35:52.484
<i>was to the South and Virginia.</i>

35:52.484 --> 35:54.402
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

35:54.402 --> 35:56.237
<i>‐ Ulysses S. Grant,</i>
<i>however,</i>

35:56.237 --> 35:59.741
<i>starts the Civil War</i>
<i>as a nobody,</i>

35:59.741 --> 36:02.035
<i>but he gets a big break</i>
<i>when the governor of Illinois</i>

36:02.035 --> 36:05.246
appoints him as commander of
one of the Illinois regiments,

36:05.246 --> 36:08.667
and that will start
his military career again.

36:09.876 --> 36:11.878
<i>‐ And so having come</i>
<i>from the tannery</i>

36:11.878 --> 36:15.215
<i>and now having this window</i>
<i>of opportunity with this war</i>

36:15.215 --> 36:17.676
to get back in the army,
to take command,

36:17.676 --> 36:20.720
he recognizes that
"I must seize it," and he does.

36:20.720 --> 36:23.181
<i>‐ Grant comes out</i>
<i>of a series of failures</i>

36:23.181 --> 36:24.808
<i>in his civilian life.</i>

36:24.808 --> 36:28.478
At one point, he has
to literally sell his watch

36:28.478 --> 36:31.606
to buy Christmas presents
for his wife and children,

36:31.606 --> 36:34.943
<i>and now all of a sudden</i>
<i>he's back in uniform.</i>

36:34.943 --> 36:36.569
<i>‐ Grant comes in</i>
<i>with a firm hand.</i>

36:36.569 --> 36:38.655
<i>He whips this regiment</i>
<i>into shape,</i>

36:38.655 --> 36:42.409
and people start realizing
maybe we've got something here.

36:43.993 --> 36:47.414
<i>‐ In the military,</i>
<i>he was home again.</i>

36:47.414 --> 36:48.915
<i>There was something</i>
<i>about the way</i>

36:48.915 --> 36:51.960
he unsheathed his sword,
the way he gave orders

36:51.960 --> 36:55.046
that people suddenly
listened to and obeyed.

36:57.006 --> 36:59.175
<i>‐ Very soon after</i>
<i>the war began,</i>

36:59.175 --> 37:03.054
<i>Grant gets orders to take</i>
<i>his men into Kentucky,</i>

37:03.054 --> 37:07.475
as much for political reasons
as for military reasons.

37:07.475 --> 37:09.811
<i>‐ Kentucky is one of</i>
<i>four slaveholding states</i>

37:09.811 --> 37:12.772
that will remain
precariously tethered

37:12.772 --> 37:14.274
to the Union
throughout the war.

37:14.274 --> 37:17.569
<i>We called those</i>
<i>the border states.</i>

37:17.569 --> 37:19.404
<i>‐ Abraham Lincoln</i>
<i>was very concerned</i>

37:19.404 --> 37:22.115
<i>about keeping Kentucky</i>
<i>in the Union.</i>

37:22.115 --> 37:24.576
He said, "To lose Kentucky
is nearly the same

37:24.576 --> 37:26.369
as to lose the whole game."

37:26.369 --> 37:27.954
<i>He thought the other</i>
<i>border states</i>

37:27.954 --> 37:30.582
<i>might follow suit as well.</i>

37:30.582 --> 37:35.170
<i>And then a Confederate army</i>
<i>marched into Kentucky,</i>

37:35.170 --> 37:39.466
<i>so Grant moves as fast as he</i>
<i>can to Paducah, Kentucky.</i>

37:39.466 --> 37:42.469
<i>[tense music]</i>

37:42.469 --> 37:49.559
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:52.437 --> 37:54.564
<i>‐ Dear Julia,</i>

37:54.564 --> 37:57.066
<i>secession flags</i>
<i>were flying through Paducah</i>

37:57.066 --> 38:00.487
<i>in anticipation</i>
<i>of Southern troops.</i>

38:00.487 --> 38:04.949
<i>Our arrival, therefore, put</i>
<i>quite a damper on their hopes.</i>

38:04.949 --> 38:11.956
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:16.795 --> 38:18.338
‐ [whispering]
Come away from the window.

38:18.338 --> 38:20.507
Those are Yankees.

38:20.507 --> 38:23.051
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:23.051 --> 38:25.345
‐ General, it's time.
Troops are moving in.

38:25.345 --> 38:32.352
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:35.355 --> 38:38.733
<i>‐ Citizens of Paducah,</i>
<i>I have come among you</i>

38:38.733 --> 38:40.652
<i>not as your enemy</i>
<i>but as your friend</i>

38:40.652 --> 38:45.365
<i>and fellow citizen,</i>
<i>not to injure or annoy you</i>

38:45.365 --> 38:47.575
<i>but to respect the rights</i>
<i>and to defend</i>

38:47.575 --> 38:52.539
<i>and enforce the rights</i>
<i>of all loyal citizens.</i>

38:52.539 --> 38:56.584
<i>‐ Grant issues a proclamation</i>
<i>to try to quell civilian fear,</i>

38:56.584 --> 38:58.920
<i>and Abraham Lincoln</i>
<i>takes note.</i>

38:58.920 --> 39:02.507
Lincoln right away saw that
proclamation and recognized,

39:02.507 --> 39:06.344
<i>"Here's a man who understands</i>
<i>people and is plain‐spoken,</i>

39:06.344 --> 39:08.680
<i>just like me."</i>

39:10.306 --> 39:13.560
<i>‐ Grant successfully</i>
<i>occupied Paducah, Kentucky</i>

39:13.560 --> 39:15.228
without a shot being fired,

39:15.228 --> 39:17.188
<i>and so he gets orders</i>
<i>to attack</i>

39:17.188 --> 39:20.275
<i>a Confederate supply link</i>
<i>on the Mississippi River</i>

39:20.275 --> 39:23.069
<i>at the small village</i>
<i>of Belmont.</i>

39:23.069 --> 39:24.946
<i>Belmont is very important.</i>

39:24.946 --> 39:28.992
It's Grant's first real test
of combat in the Civil War.

39:28.992 --> 39:30.785
<i>‐ My dear Julia,</i>

39:30.785 --> 39:33.705
<i>what you are to look out for</i>
<i>I cannot tell you,</i>

39:33.705 --> 39:36.416
<i>but your husband will never</i>
<i>disgrace you</i>

39:36.416 --> 39:39.043
<i>nor leave a defeated field.</i>

39:39.043 --> 39:46.050
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:02.191 --> 40:05.069
‐ Captain, flush
these rebels out now.

40:05.069 --> 40:06.112
Go on.
Go.

40:06.112 --> 40:07.363
‐ Yes, sir.

40:07.363 --> 40:08.656
<i>‐ Whoo, let them</i>
<i>taste this steel!</i>

40:08.656 --> 40:10.825
<i>‐ Form up!</i>
<i>On me!</i>

40:10.825 --> 40:13.828
[all shouting]

40:13.828 --> 40:16.831
[gunfire]

40:16.831 --> 40:19.959
[all shouting]

40:28.927 --> 40:30.595
‐ Find the ammunition, boys!

40:30.595 --> 40:33.139
<i>[tense music]</i>

40:33.139 --> 40:35.350
<i>‐ The Confederates abandoned</i>
<i>their camp,</i>

40:35.350 --> 40:38.728
<i>and these Union forces,</i>
<i>these are guys who just fought</i>

40:38.728 --> 40:41.648
<i>their first battle,</i>
<i>very light casualties,</i>

40:41.648 --> 40:45.360
and so they are euphoric
at this point.

40:45.360 --> 40:48.863
<i>‐ Grant has won, seemingly,</i>
<i>a significant victory here,</i>

40:48.863 --> 40:52.158
but his troops
lose all discipline.

40:52.158 --> 40:55.453
[horse whinnies]
<i>‐ Don't mind if I do!</i>

40:55.453 --> 40:58.081
‐ Show me that blood
on your hands!

40:58.081 --> 41:00.291
[all shouting]

41:00.291 --> 41:04.087
‐ Hey, boys,
look what I found.

41:04.087 --> 41:10.051
‐ Captain, control your men!
‐ Yes, sir!

41:10.051 --> 41:12.136
‐ Now I can hit them Yankees.

41:12.136 --> 41:13.930
[gunshot]

41:13.930 --> 41:15.682
‐ Run!

41:15.682 --> 41:16.516
[horse whinnying]

41:19.310 --> 41:21.604
[all shouting]

41:21.604 --> 41:24.148
‐ Captain,
control your men!

41:24.148 --> 41:26.109
‐ Yes, sir!

41:26.109 --> 41:28.778
<i>‐ At Grant's first</i>
<i>engagement at Belmont,</i>

41:28.778 --> 41:31.531
<i>the Confederates</i>
<i>counterattacked.</i>

41:31.531 --> 41:34.534
[gunfire]

41:34.534 --> 41:36.619
[all shouting]

41:36.619 --> 41:38.287
‐ Into the trees!

41:38.287 --> 41:40.665
We cut our way in.
We cut our way out.

41:40.665 --> 41:43.334
‐ Keep your head down!
‐ Into the trees!

41:43.334 --> 41:45.003
<i>‐ They organized</i>
<i>a fighting retreat</i>

41:45.003 --> 41:46.671
<i>north to the riverboats</i>

41:46.671 --> 41:49.465
that were going to give them
their means of escape.

41:49.465 --> 41:51.843
<i>Grant was the last man</i>
<i>to get on board ship.</i>

41:51.843 --> 41:53.678
<i>The boat had already untied</i>

41:53.678 --> 41:55.680
<i>and was starting to drift</i>
<i>out into the river,</i>

41:55.680 --> 41:58.224
<i>and Grant actually</i>
<i>rode his horse</i>

41:58.224 --> 42:01.519
<i>across the gangplank</i>
<i>onto the riverboat.</i>

42:01.519 --> 42:04.522
<i>It was an amazing feat</i>
<i>of horsemanship,</i>

42:04.522 --> 42:07.525
<i>and Grant, in his typical</i>
<i>self‐deprecating style,</i>

42:07.525 --> 42:11.529
he gave all the credit
to the horse.

42:11.529 --> 42:13.990
<i>He made some serious mistakes.</i>

42:13.990 --> 42:18.536
<i>He lost control of his men,</i>
<i>but he is learning,</i>

42:18.536 --> 42:19.996
and coming out
of the Battle of Belmont,

42:19.996 --> 42:21.789
he's looking
for the next fight.

42:21.789 --> 42:25.043
<i>[tense music]</i>

42:25.043 --> 42:27.295
<i>‐ In the early years</i>
<i>of the war</i>

42:27.295 --> 42:30.548
<i>there are really</i>
<i>two distinct theaters.</i>

42:30.548 --> 42:32.592
<i>You have the eastern theater,</i>

42:32.592 --> 42:36.345
where a series of different
Union commanders prove

42:36.345 --> 42:40.058
<i>incapable of really putting</i>
<i>the pressure on the South</i>

42:40.058 --> 42:43.895
<i>that President Lincoln</i>
<i>wants to see,</i>

42:43.895 --> 42:45.688
and then you have
the western theater,

42:45.688 --> 42:47.482
which is where Grant is.

42:47.482 --> 42:49.984
<i>‐ In that western theater,</i>
<i>the Union's strategy</i>

42:49.984 --> 42:51.736
<i>is going to be</i>

42:51.736 --> 42:54.864
to occupy key transportation
facilities in the west,

42:54.864 --> 42:57.950
open up the entire Mississippi
if they can,

42:57.950 --> 43:00.369
<i>and it was rather simple</i>
<i>to look on a map</i>

43:00.369 --> 43:03.206
<i>where the Confederate</i>
<i>strong points were</i>

43:03.206 --> 43:05.917
and see where
the dominoes might fall.

43:05.917 --> 43:09.087
<i>Grant could plainly see</i>
<i>that the most obvious ones‐‐</i>

43:09.087 --> 43:10.713
<i>the northernmost ones‐‐</i>

43:10.713 --> 43:13.883
<i>were clearly</i>
<i>Forts Henry and Donelson.</i>

43:13.883 --> 43:15.718
<i>They commanded key rivers,</i>

43:15.718 --> 43:17.720
<i>and he could use</i>
<i>those key rivers</i>

43:17.720 --> 43:22.433
<i>to advance directly</i>
<i>into the Confederacy.</i>

43:22.433 --> 43:25.353
<i>‐ Grant wants to get</i>
<i>this war moving.</i>

43:25.353 --> 43:28.815
He doesn't believe sitting in
garrison is gonna win anything,

43:28.815 --> 43:31.442
<i>so he makes a proposal</i>
<i>to his commander,</i>

43:31.442 --> 43:33.236
<i>General Henry Halleck.</i>

43:33.236 --> 43:40.284
<i>♪ ♪</i>

43:51.796 --> 43:56.050
‐ General Halleck,
it's an honor.

44:05.601 --> 44:08.479
‐ State briefly
the nature of your business.

44:10.565 --> 44:12.817
‐ My division is stationed
here in Carroll

44:12.817 --> 44:14.986
on the Cumberland River,

44:14.986 --> 44:16.946
where we've been sizing up
a naval assault

44:16.946 --> 44:21.576
on two enemy forts,
Fort Henry and Fort Donelson.

44:36.674 --> 44:39.135
‐ Continue.

44:41.470 --> 44:42.805
‐ Fort Henry is badly sited

44:42.805 --> 44:44.765
and vulnerable from the water.

44:44.765 --> 44:46.017
Fort Donelson is stronger

44:46.017 --> 44:48.853
but commanded
by General John Floyd,

44:48.853 --> 44:50.563
and he's no soldier.

44:52.064 --> 44:53.858
I believe if I can
take both forts,

44:53.858 --> 44:59.155
we can advance as far
as Nashville and Alabama.

44:59.155 --> 45:01.949
‐ A combined naval assault?

45:01.949 --> 45:05.203
‐ The victories would
be yours, sir.

45:06.329 --> 45:07.705
‐ Thank you.

45:14.420 --> 45:17.548
But when I wish
to consult you on a subject,

45:17.548 --> 45:19.383
I will notify you.

45:19.383 --> 45:23.054
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

45:23.054 --> 45:24.597
‐ Yes, sir.

45:24.597 --> 45:29.602
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:29.602 --> 45:32.855
[door opening and shutting]

45:32.855 --> 45:37.068
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:37.068 --> 45:39.362
<i>‐ They called Halleck</i>
<i>"Old Brains."</i>

45:39.362 --> 45:41.906
<i>They don't call him</i>
<i>that for nothing.</i>

45:41.906 --> 45:45.284
He wants everything done
absolutely by the book,

45:45.284 --> 45:49.205
<i>and Grant is not</i>
<i>a by‐the‐book kind of guy.</i>

45:49.205 --> 45:51.249
<i>No limelight, no fanfare,</i>

45:51.249 --> 45:53.584
and forget the pomp
and circumstance.

45:53.584 --> 45:57.880
We're just gonna get it done,
and so the two clash.

45:57.880 --> 45:59.924
<i>Grant,</i>
<i>with his bulldog mentality,</i>

45:59.924 --> 46:03.344
<i>immediately turns to what</i>
<i>I call his naval soul mate,</i>

46:03.344 --> 46:04.929
<i>Andrew H. Foote,</i>

46:04.929 --> 46:07.265
<i>the naval commander</i>
<i>of the western flotilla</i>

46:07.265 --> 46:09.100
<i>with ironclad gunboats.</i>

46:09.100 --> 46:11.435
<i>‐ So the two of them</i>
<i>jointly made a proposal</i>

46:11.435 --> 46:14.772
to General Halleck
to move against Fort Henry.

46:14.772 --> 46:17.108
<i>‐ They're begging Halleck,</i>
<i>prodding Halleck.</i>

46:17.108 --> 46:19.068
"Please, turn us loose.
Let us go,"

46:19.068 --> 46:21.404
<i>and it's only by</i>
<i>the slimmest margins</i>

46:21.404 --> 46:25.199
<i>that Halleck allows</i>
<i>Grant to attack.</i>

46:25.199 --> 46:27.660
<i>‐ It's very different</i>
<i>to be in charge.</i>

46:27.660 --> 46:31.330
<i>Command is</i>
<i>an extraordinary privilege</i>

46:31.330 --> 46:32.957
and the weight
of responsibility

46:32.957 --> 46:35.126
is very much on your shoulders,

46:35.126 --> 46:39.880
<i>and Grant experiences this</i>
<i>as he approaches Fort Henry.</i>

46:39.880 --> 46:42.008
<i>[tense music]</i>

46:42.008 --> 46:43.801
<i>‐ So February the 6th,</i>

46:43.801 --> 46:46.429
<i>Foote's gunboats begin</i>
<i>to shell Fort Henry.</i>

46:46.429 --> 46:48.431
<i>‐ The infantry's gonna get</i>
<i>behind each fort,</i>

46:48.431 --> 46:50.474
<i>seal in</i>
<i>the Confederate defenders</i>

46:50.474 --> 46:54.812
while the navy just pummels
Fort Henry into submission.

46:55.688 --> 46:59.734
<i>‐ Most of the Confederates</i>
<i>had already evacuated.</i>

46:59.734 --> 47:02.778
Fort Henry surrenders
before Grant's men

47:02.778 --> 47:05.114
even get close to the fort.

47:05.114 --> 47:07.992
<i>The capture of Fort Henry</i>
<i>was significant,</i>

47:07.992 --> 47:12.496
but Grant is not gonna sit
and rest on his laurels.

47:12.496 --> 47:16.625
<i>Fort Donelson was only</i>
<i>about 12 miles to the east.</i>

47:16.625 --> 47:19.420
<i>He keeps the ball moving.</i>

47:19.420 --> 47:21.714
‐ Grant's thinking,
"All I have to do is say boo,

47:21.714 --> 47:23.841
and they'll‐‐
they'll surrender,"

47:23.841 --> 47:26.677
and, um, it doesn't
really happen that way.

47:26.677 --> 47:28.512
[booming]

47:28.512 --> 47:31.390
<i>‐ Fort Donelson was in</i>
<i>a much better position,</i>

47:31.390 --> 47:35.353
<i>much better engineered</i>
<i>than Fort Henry.</i>

47:35.353 --> 47:38.689
An artillery duel began between
the fort and his gunboats,

47:38.689 --> 47:41.525
and in short,
the fort won.

47:41.525 --> 47:44.403
‐ The Confederates came out
of the fort to counterattack...

47:44.403 --> 47:46.447
<i>[all shouting]</i>

47:46.447 --> 47:49.367
And the first thing
Grant does is not panic.

47:49.367 --> 47:50.701
<i>That's a pattern with Grant.</i>

47:50.701 --> 47:52.453
<i>No matter what happens,</i>

47:52.453 --> 47:55.331
<i>no matter how bad it gets,</i>
<i>Grant doesn't panic.</i>

47:55.331 --> 47:56.540
‐ In the midst of the battle,

47:56.540 --> 47:58.000
which is truly chaotic,

47:58.000 --> 48:00.044
<i>Grant keeps his wits</i>
<i>about him.</i>

48:00.044 --> 48:01.587
<i>He actually thinks.</i>

48:01.587 --> 48:05.216
<i>He can take input.</i>
<i>He can change his mind.</i>

48:05.216 --> 48:07.343
<i>‐ At Fort Donelson,</i>
<i>Grant will figure out</i>

48:07.343 --> 48:09.720
these Confederates are moving
with their knapsacks.

48:09.720 --> 48:11.180
They're not intending
on going back.

48:11.180 --> 48:12.890
They're getting out of here.

48:12.890 --> 48:15.893
[booming]

48:15.893 --> 48:18.771
[all shouting]

48:18.771 --> 48:21.774
[gunfire]

48:21.774 --> 48:24.819
[booming]

48:26.404 --> 48:29.615
‐ Bring me that prisoner.
Show me his bag.

48:32.701 --> 48:35.538
This looks like
two days' rations...

48:35.538 --> 48:37.748
No, three.

48:37.748 --> 48:38.874
‐ Looks like
they're settling in

48:38.874 --> 48:40.251
to hold their position.

48:40.251 --> 48:42.420
‐ Looks like that,
but it's a retreat.

48:42.420 --> 48:45.256
Three days of rations is just
enough to get to Nashville.

48:45.256 --> 48:48.592
‐ Sir, we should reinforce the
right and wait till nightfall.

48:48.592 --> 48:50.928
‐ If we wait,
they'll have time to escape.

48:50.928 --> 48:54.974
We got to attack now,
and we can take this victory.

48:54.974 --> 48:56.684
Form your lines.

48:56.684 --> 48:58.436
‐ Sir.

48:58.436 --> 49:01.313
Form your lines!

49:01.313 --> 49:03.065
Form your lines!

49:03.065 --> 49:05.734
[booming]

49:05.734 --> 49:07.695
‐ Prepare to advance!

49:10.656 --> 49:13.617
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

49:13.617 --> 49:20.666
<i>♪ ♪</i>

49:50.905 --> 49:52.323
[booming]
[horse whinnying]

49:52.323 --> 49:53.908
[all laughing]

49:53.908 --> 49:57.745
[booming]

49:57.745 --> 50:02.875
‐ They want an armistice
and terms for surrender.

50:02.875 --> 50:05.586
We've broken their defenses,
surrounded the fort,

50:05.586 --> 50:08.380
and outnumber them
almost two to one.

50:08.380 --> 50:11.342
It's checkmate.

50:11.342 --> 50:14.428
‐ Who signed the note?
‐ General Buckner.

50:15.554 --> 50:19.683
‐ Oh, Buckner.

50:19.683 --> 50:23.187
I know him
from West Point.

50:23.187 --> 50:26.106
He paid off one of my debts
back in New York.

50:26.106 --> 50:28.984
Saved me, really.

50:28.984 --> 50:32.029
Helped me get back
to my family.

50:32.029 --> 50:34.782
‐ Then what are your terms?

50:39.286 --> 50:43.249
‐ Immediate
and unconditional surrender,

50:43.249 --> 50:46.085
or we fire on their works.

50:49.380 --> 50:51.966
<i>[tense music]</i>

50:51.966 --> 50:55.219
<i>‐ At Fort Donelson, Grant</i>
<i>had organized a counterattack.</i>

50:55.219 --> 50:58.055
The Confederates withdrew back
into the fort,

50:58.055 --> 51:00.349
<i>and they're trapped.</i>

51:00.349 --> 51:01.892
<i>‐ When Grant</i>
<i>got the message,</i>

51:01.892 --> 51:03.644
<i>"Hey, I want to talk</i>
<i>about surrender,"</i>

51:03.644 --> 51:06.564
<i>the Confederate command</i>
<i>situation at Fort Donelson</i>

51:06.564 --> 51:09.817
had been an absolute
comedy of errors.

51:09.817 --> 51:14.113
<i>There had been three general</i>
<i>officers inside Fort Donelson,</i>

51:14.113 --> 51:17.616
<i>John Floyd,</i>
<i>Gideon Pillow,</i>

51:17.616 --> 51:21.287
<i>and Grant's old friend,</i>
<i>Simon Bolivar Buckner.</i>

51:21.287 --> 51:25.666
But when the idea comes
to surrender, Floyd says,

51:25.666 --> 51:27.585
"There is nobody
in the Confederacy

51:27.585 --> 51:29.545
that they want worse than me,"

51:29.545 --> 51:31.422
and so he says,
"I'm not surrendering,"

51:31.422 --> 51:34.258
<i>and he'll get out of Dodge.</i>

51:34.258 --> 51:36.594
<i>The second in command</i>
<i>is Gideon Pillow.</i>

51:36.594 --> 51:39.888
<i>He thinks he's the greatest</i>
<i>military commander ever,</i>

51:39.888 --> 51:41.432
<i>and Pillow says,</i>

51:41.432 --> 51:43.100
"They want me as well,
so I'm not surrendering,"

51:43.100 --> 51:45.728
so he gets out as well,
turning the command over

51:45.728 --> 51:49.106
<i>to the third in command,</i>
<i>Simon Buckner.</i>

51:49.106 --> 51:51.775
<i>‐ Surrender</i>
<i>was the proper thing.</i>

51:51.775 --> 51:55.487
<i>I rode to Buckner's</i>
<i>headquarters.</i>

51:55.487 --> 51:59.992
[door opening]

51:59.992 --> 52:01.994
[door closing]

52:01.994 --> 52:03.662
General Buckner.

52:09.376 --> 52:11.003
‐ You would not have
taken the fort so easily

52:11.003 --> 52:12.713
if I'd been in command.

52:13.672 --> 52:15.341
‐ You're right.

52:15.341 --> 52:17.343
I would have
done it differently.

52:21.305 --> 52:24.308
I assume Floyd
and Pillow got away.

52:24.308 --> 52:28.646
‐ Last night,
yellow bastards.

52:28.646 --> 52:31.315
Pillow feared
you'd want him prisoner.

52:31.315 --> 52:33.525
‐ In my humblest opinion,
he's more valuable to me

52:33.525 --> 52:35.152
as a Southern general.

52:42.868 --> 52:46.497
‐ Well, here we are,
old friend.

52:46.497 --> 52:48.582
‐ Here we are.

52:48.582 --> 52:50.376
‐ About the terms you sent.

52:50.376 --> 52:53.003
‐ No terms.

52:53.003 --> 52:55.214
Immediate and
unconditional surrender...

52:57.675 --> 52:59.593
Old friend.

52:59.593 --> 53:02.513
<i>[tense music]</i>

53:02.513 --> 53:09.603
<i>♪ ♪</i>

53:15.693 --> 53:19.822
<i>‐ The first real victory</i>
<i>for the United States</i>

53:19.822 --> 53:24.910
<i>occurred at Fort Donelson</i>
<i>in February of 1862</i>

53:24.910 --> 53:27.788
<i>courtesy of Ulysses S. Grant.</i>

53:27.788 --> 53:30.374
<i>U.S. Grant.</i>

53:30.374 --> 53:35.713
<i>Useless Grant became</i>
<i>Unconditional Surrender Grant,</i>

53:35.713 --> 53:39.425
and that thrilled
the northern population.

53:39.425 --> 53:42.261
<i>It was big news</i>
<i>because nothing good</i>

53:42.261 --> 53:46.265
<i>had been happening</i>
<i>for the Union in the war.</i>

53:46.265 --> 53:48.767
<i>‐ In the eastern theater</i>
<i>of the war,</i>

53:48.767 --> 53:50.394
<i>Lincoln is dealing</i>
<i>with one whining,</i>

53:50.394 --> 53:53.939
<i>procrastinating general</i>
<i>after another,</i>

53:53.939 --> 53:55.774
but here's
this Ulysses S. Grant

53:55.774 --> 53:58.068
out west who's
winning battle after battle,

53:58.068 --> 54:00.070
<i>and Lincoln is thrilled.</i>

54:00.070 --> 54:02.906
<i>He rushes to sign the order</i>
<i>promoting Grant</i>

54:02.906 --> 54:04.533
<i>to major general.</i>

54:04.533 --> 54:07.119
<i>‐ The first significant</i>
<i>Northern victory</i>

54:07.119 --> 54:11.915
of the Civil War will launch
Grant to national prominence.

54:11.915 --> 54:14.835
<i>During the aftermath of</i>
<i>the Battle at Fort Donelson,</i>

54:14.835 --> 54:18.130
<i>a war correspondent</i>
<i>painted a picture of Grant</i>

54:18.130 --> 54:19.673
<i>mounted on horseback,</i>

54:19.673 --> 54:22.760
<i>and in his mouth</i>
<i>is the stub of a cigar.</i>

54:22.760 --> 54:24.803
<i>As this was the first great</i>
<i>Northern victory</i>

54:24.803 --> 54:26.764
<i>of the Civil War, fans‐‐</i>

54:26.764 --> 54:31.477
admirers‐‐
sent him 5,000 cigars,

54:31.477 --> 54:33.812
and so he started
smoking these things,

54:33.812 --> 54:37.941
<i>and Grant would smoke</i>
<i>upwards of 20 of these a day.</i>

54:39.985 --> 54:42.738
<i>‐ For Grant,</i>
<i>the first year goes good.</i>

54:42.738 --> 54:46.492
If there's a rookie
of the year for the Union side,

54:46.492 --> 54:47.951
<i>it's Ulysses S. Grant.</i>

54:47.951 --> 54:50.787
<i>Nobody's wining</i>
<i>the victories like he is.</i>

54:50.787 --> 54:53.999
<i>‐ He realized again that</i>
<i>he had a gift for this.</i>

54:53.999 --> 54:57.461
He was very, very good
at battlefield command,

54:57.461 --> 54:58.837
and then beyond that,

54:58.837 --> 55:02.674
at battlefield strategy
and tactics.

55:02.674 --> 55:05.344
<i>‐ Grant has captured the first</i>
<i>of three armies</i>

55:05.344 --> 55:08.138
that he will capture
over the course of the war,

55:08.138 --> 55:11.099
<i>and he has now opened</i>
<i>the Cumberland River</i>

55:11.099 --> 55:14.478
<i>so Union naval forces</i>
<i>and land forces</i>

55:14.478 --> 55:18.398
<i>can make their way south deep</i>
<i>into the Confederacy.</i>

55:18.398 --> 55:20.484
<i>‐ Dear Julia,</i>

55:20.484 --> 55:22.986
<i>soon I hope</i>
<i>to move from here,</i>

55:22.986 --> 55:25.489
<i>and when I do,</i>
<i>there will probably</i>

55:25.489 --> 55:28.825
<i>be the greatest battle</i>
<i>fought of the war.</i>

55:31.662 --> 55:34.957
<i>I have no doubt of the result.</i>

55:38.710 --> 55:43.382
‐ Yah, yah!
Ha!

55:43.382 --> 55:46.093
<i>‐ The enemy was</i>
<i>in force in Corinth,</i>

55:46.093 --> 55:48.679
<i>the junction of the two</i>
<i>most important railroads</i>

55:48.679 --> 55:50.681
<i>in the Mississippi Valley.</i>

55:50.681 --> 55:53.058
<i>If we obtained possession</i>
<i>of Corinth,</i>

55:53.058 --> 55:54.851
<i>the enemy would have</i>
<i>no railroad</i>

55:54.851 --> 55:59.022
<i>for the transportation</i>
<i>of armies or supplies.</i>

55:59.022 --> 56:01.441
‐ Grant is thinking,
"How do I stay two steps ahead?

56:01.441 --> 56:02.901
"How do I retain
the initiative?

56:02.901 --> 56:05.279
How do I keep the enemy
reacting to me?"

56:05.279 --> 56:07.573
<i>The war in the east</i>
<i>is going badly,</i>

56:07.573 --> 56:10.075
<i>so everything</i>
<i>is under a microscope,</i>

56:10.075 --> 56:12.703
<i>but in the west,</i>
<i>with the first big victories</i>

56:12.703 --> 56:14.246
<i>at Forts Henry and Donelson,</i>

56:14.246 --> 56:16.081
<i>now all of a sudden</i>
<i>the Tennessee</i>

56:16.081 --> 56:19.167
<i>and Cumberland Rivers are open</i>
<i>to invade the South,</i>

56:19.167 --> 56:21.878
and this is what
Grant seizes upon.

56:21.878 --> 56:24.298
<i>‐ Knowing that the enemy's</i>
<i>fortifying Corinth</i>

56:24.298 --> 56:26.508
<i>and collecting an army there,</i>

56:26.508 --> 56:28.844
<i>I at once put all</i>
<i>the troops in motion</i>

56:28.844 --> 56:30.637
<i>for Pittsburg Landing.</i>

56:30.637 --> 56:34.224
<i>[tense music]</i>

56:34.224 --> 56:36.310
<i>‐ Pittsburg Landing</i>
<i>is a staging area</i>

56:36.310 --> 56:38.186
<i>to attack at Corinth.</i>

56:38.186 --> 56:39.896
General Halleck warns Grant,

56:39.896 --> 56:42.774
"Don't bring on an engagement.
Don't start anything.

56:42.774 --> 56:45.986
Don't pick a fight
until everything is ready."

56:45.986 --> 56:48.864
<i>‐ The army had arrived</i>
<i>with one of Grant's</i>

56:48.864 --> 56:51.325
<i>core commanders,</i>
<i>William Tecumseh Sherman.</i>

56:51.325 --> 56:53.869
<i>Sherman was a friend</i>
<i>of Grant's at West Point,</i>

56:53.869 --> 56:56.496
<i>but they had not worked</i>
<i>together before,</i>

56:56.496 --> 56:59.750
and many of Grant's men
were absolutely green.

56:59.750 --> 57:03.503
<i>Some had just received their</i>
<i>weapons a few days earlier.</i>

57:03.503 --> 57:07.633
<i>So Grant's intention is to get</i>
<i>his men some training</i>

57:07.633 --> 57:10.510
and wait there
for another Union army

57:10.510 --> 57:12.137
<i>under the command</i>
<i>of Don Carlos Buell</i>

57:12.137 --> 57:15.974
<i>to get there</i>
<i>and then set out to Corinth.</i>

57:15.974 --> 57:18.393
‐ So the idea
of fighting a battle

57:18.393 --> 57:19.936
never enters Grant's mind

57:19.936 --> 57:22.856
at Pittsburg Landing,
and the scene is set

57:22.856 --> 57:26.401
<i>for what would become</i>
<i>this bloodbath of Shiloh.</i>

57:26.401 --> 57:32.783
<i>♪ ♪</i>

57:32.783 --> 57:36.244
[indistinct chatter]

57:36.244 --> 57:38.163
‐ Sir, do you want
the new men digging trenches?

57:38.163 --> 57:39.790
‐ I don't intend
to be here long enough.

57:39.790 --> 57:41.333
The men are raw.

57:41.333 --> 57:43.794
They need practice with guns,
not with shovels.

57:45.962 --> 57:47.214
Sherman.

57:47.214 --> 57:50.884
‐ Sam.
‐ Activity?

57:50.884 --> 57:52.219
‐ The Rebs
stick their noses out,

57:52.219 --> 57:53.887
and we keep slapping them.

57:53.887 --> 57:55.889
Whipped them
in a skirmish yesterday.

57:55.889 --> 57:59.142
‐ And General Buell's men?
‐ They're three days out.

58:02.479 --> 58:05.899
‐ We'll move on Corinth
when he gets here.

58:05.899 --> 58:07.401
‐ If we go down here‐‐

58:07.401 --> 58:09.236
‐ Yeah.
‐ The whole way down‐‐

58:09.236 --> 58:12.656
<i>‐ To General Halleck,</i>
<i>the temper of the rebel troops</i>

58:12.656 --> 58:14.991
<i>is such that there</i>
<i>is little doubt that Corinth</i>

58:14.991 --> 58:20.122
<i>will fall much more easily</i>
<i>than Fort Donelson did.</i>

58:20.122 --> 58:22.457
<i>‐ Grant's major fault early</i>
<i>in the war</i>

58:22.457 --> 58:25.836
<i>is this overconfidence.</i>

58:25.836 --> 58:27.504
He thinks,
"If anything happens,

58:27.504 --> 58:31.007
I'm gonna start it,"
and it comes back to bite him.

58:31.633 --> 58:33.343
<i>‐ Their commander at Corinth,</i>

58:33.343 --> 58:34.886
<i>General Albert</i>
<i>Sidney Johnston,</i>

58:34.886 --> 58:37.639
<i>has been doing nothing</i>
<i>but retreat.</i>

58:37.639 --> 58:40.892
<i>If he cannot regain the</i>
<i>initiative and defeat Grant,</i>

58:40.892 --> 58:42.686
<i>it likely will mean</i>

58:42.686 --> 58:45.564
<i>the Confederacy will lose</i>
<i>the Mississippi River.</i>

58:45.564 --> 58:48.150
<i>Johnston really believes that</i>
<i>the war itself</i>

58:48.150 --> 58:50.152
<i>may be at stake,</i>

58:50.152 --> 58:54.531
so Johnston decides to organize
a counterattack against Grant.

58:55.574 --> 58:57.409
<i>‐ Johnston knows that Grant's</i>
<i>army's tucked up</i>

58:57.409 --> 58:59.202
<i>into Pittsburg Landing,</i>

58:59.202 --> 59:02.622
<i>which is a cul‐de‐sac</i>
<i>along the Tennessee River</i>

59:02.622 --> 59:05.417
<i>in between two major creeks.</i>

59:05.417 --> 59:08.336
<i>It seems like a good place</i>
<i>to camp the army.</i>

59:08.336 --> 59:09.671
There are good springs here.

59:09.671 --> 59:11.047
There are creeks.
We can get water.

59:11.047 --> 59:13.633
It's good,
level camping ground,

59:13.633 --> 59:16.762
<i>but the Confederate plan</i>
<i>is to trap the Union army</i>

59:16.762 --> 59:18.972
<i>in this cul‐de‐sac</i>

59:18.972 --> 59:23.894
<i>and to destroy the Union army</i>
<i>with one massive attack.</i>

59:23.894 --> 59:25.896
<i>[tense music]</i>

59:25.896 --> 59:29.483
And so Johnston gambles,
and he says,

59:29.483 --> 59:31.902
<i>"We must roll</i>
<i>the iron dice of battle.</i>

59:31.902 --> 59:34.863
We must conquer or perish."

59:34.863 --> 59:37.824
[thunder cracking]

59:37.824 --> 59:40.869
[rain pattering]

59:43.455 --> 59:46.208
<i>‐ Grant's camp</i>
<i>at Pittsburg Landing</i>

59:46.208 --> 59:49.419
<i>was right near</i>
<i>a small wooden church.</i>

59:49.419 --> 59:52.339
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

59:52.339 --> 59:55.217
<i>It's one of the only landmarks</i>
<i>in the entire vicinity.</i>

59:55.217 --> 59:57.093
<i>♪ ♪</i>

59:57.093 --> 1:00:01.097
<i>It was called Shiloh Church.</i>

1:00:01.097 --> 1:00:04.935
<i>Shiloh is translated</i>
<i>as "place of peace."</i>

1:00:04.935 --> 1:00:12.025
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:00:29.960 --> 1:00:32.963
<i>[tense music]</i>

1:00:32.963 --> 1:00:39.970
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:01:15.338 --> 1:01:16.590
[gunshot]

1:01:16.590 --> 1:01:18.383
[man grunts]

1:01:18.383 --> 1:01:20.385
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:01:20.385 --> 1:01:22.929
[gunshot]
‐ Rebs!

1:01:22.929 --> 1:01:25.724
‐ Fire!
[gunfire]

1:01:25.724 --> 1:01:27.893
‐ Rebs!

1:01:27.893 --> 1:01:29.895
We got them from the woods!
Rebs!

1:01:29.895 --> 1:01:34.274
[gunfire]

1:01:34.274 --> 1:01:36.026
‐ In the woods!

1:01:36.026 --> 1:01:39.029
[all shouting]
‐ Rebs in the woods!

1:01:39.029 --> 1:01:41.031
[gunfire]

1:01:41.031 --> 1:01:42.866
‐ Rebs!

1:01:42.866 --> 1:01:44.284
They're coming from the woods!

1:01:44.284 --> 1:01:45.952
‐ Rebs in the woods!
‐ Rebs!

1:01:45.952 --> 1:01:48.204
[all shouting]

1:01:48.204 --> 1:01:49.998
‐ Wait, wait, what?

1:01:49.998 --> 1:01:51.750
<i>‐ Move, move!</i>

1:01:51.750 --> 1:01:54.669
‐ [breathing heavily]

1:01:54.669 --> 1:01:57.672
[all shouting]

1:01:57.672 --> 1:02:00.675
[gunfire]

1:02:00.675 --> 1:02:07.098
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:02:07.098 --> 1:02:08.391
<i>‐ Report.</i>

1:02:08.391 --> 1:02:10.518
‐ Skirmishes, sir.
That's all.

1:02:10.518 --> 1:02:12.479
[gunfire]

1:02:12.479 --> 1:02:14.522
‐ These are not
damn skirmishes.

1:02:14.522 --> 1:02:17.525
My God, we are attacked.
Form a line and hold it.

1:02:17.525 --> 1:02:19.444
[booming]

1:02:19.444 --> 1:02:22.781
[all shouting]

1:02:22.781 --> 1:02:25.533
[gunfire]

1:02:26.660 --> 1:02:29.454
‐ Ammunition!

1:02:29.454 --> 1:02:31.498
<i>‐ Grant is not at Shiloh.</i>

1:02:31.498 --> 1:02:34.250
<i>Grant is actually</i>
<i>having breakfast 9 miles north</i>

1:02:34.250 --> 1:02:37.253
<i>in his quarters</i>
<i>at the Cherry Mansion.</i>

1:02:37.253 --> 1:02:44.344
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:02:45.762 --> 1:02:50.558
[booming]

1:02:50.558 --> 1:02:53.520
‐ Gentlemen...

1:02:53.520 --> 1:02:56.106
the ball is in motion.

1:02:56.106 --> 1:02:59.818
<i>[tense music]</i>

1:02:59.818 --> 1:03:02.570
‐ Fire!
[booming]

1:03:06.992 --> 1:03:10.120
[indistinct chatter]

1:03:10.120 --> 1:03:13.123
‐ Let's get
these boys moving.

1:03:13.123 --> 1:03:16.251
Form them into regiments.

1:03:16.251 --> 1:03:19.796
I don't care what regiments
they used to be in.

1:03:19.796 --> 1:03:21.506
Make new ones.

1:03:21.506 --> 1:03:23.883
‐ Yes, sir.

1:03:23.883 --> 1:03:25.593
‐ Come on, boys,
form up!

1:03:25.593 --> 1:03:26.970
On me!
‐ Form up, regiment two.

1:03:26.970 --> 1:03:30.223
Fall in!

1:03:30.223 --> 1:03:31.641
‐ Buell won't get here
till nightfall,

1:03:31.641 --> 1:03:35.520
and Wallace is still
six miles north.

1:03:35.520 --> 1:03:37.939
‐ Order Wallace to come here
at once with his men.

1:03:37.939 --> 1:03:40.859
Sherman?
‐ No news.

1:03:40.859 --> 1:03:42.861
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:03:42.861 --> 1:03:45.363
<i>‐ On the first day</i>
<i>of the Battle of Shiloh,</i>

1:03:45.363 --> 1:03:47.824
<i>about 40,000</i>
<i>Confederate soldiers</i>

1:03:47.824 --> 1:03:52.787
<i>surprise the Union army</i>
<i>and begin pushing forward.</i>

1:03:52.787 --> 1:03:55.248
It is the largest attack
in American history

1:03:55.248 --> 1:03:57.625
up to that time.

1:03:57.625 --> 1:04:00.336
<i>‐ When Grant finally got</i>
<i>to Pittsburg Landing,</i>

1:04:00.336 --> 1:04:02.005
officers didn't know
where their men were.

1:04:02.005 --> 1:04:04.382
Their men didn't know
where the units were.

1:04:04.382 --> 1:04:08.470
<i>‐ Grant immediately begins</i>
<i>to assess the situation,</i>

1:04:08.470 --> 1:04:12.348
<i>and it's almost as</i>
<i>if battle clarified his mind,</i>

1:04:12.348 --> 1:04:14.976
and he could see the central
thing he needed to do,

1:04:14.976 --> 1:04:17.395
<i>to remain calm,</i>

1:04:17.395 --> 1:04:20.982
<i>to collect soldiers who have</i>
<i>straggled back into the area,</i>

1:04:20.982 --> 1:04:25.403
<i>and begin to plug</i>
<i>this defensive line.</i>

1:04:25.403 --> 1:04:28.406
[hooves clopping]

1:04:28.406 --> 1:04:31.409
<i>[tense music]</i>

1:04:31.409 --> 1:04:38.500
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:04:40.210 --> 1:04:44.672
[horses whinnying]

1:04:44.672 --> 1:04:47.217
‐ Hurt bad, Private?

1:04:47.217 --> 1:04:49.636
‐ It's only a scratch, sir.

1:04:49.636 --> 1:04:51.471
‐ So you can fight?

1:04:51.471 --> 1:04:54.724
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:04:54.724 --> 1:04:56.476
Come on now, boys.

1:04:56.476 --> 1:04:59.646
Pitch in.
I'm right behind you.

1:04:59.646 --> 1:05:03.775
[booming]

1:05:03.775 --> 1:05:05.860
<i>‐ Grant makes his way</i>
<i>around the battlefield,</i>

1:05:05.860 --> 1:05:08.238
<i>not caught up in the chaos,</i>

1:05:08.238 --> 1:05:10.156
<i>thinking,</i>
<i>"Where are my commanders?</i>

1:05:10.156 --> 1:05:12.075
What's their assessment of
the fight and how it's going,

1:05:12.075 --> 1:05:14.744
and what can I do
to assist them?"

1:05:14.744 --> 1:05:21.709
‐ If Pittsburg Landing falls,
Grant knows his army is gone.

1:05:21.709 --> 1:05:25.296
<i>‐ If the Confederate plan</i>
<i>is to trap the Union army</i>

1:05:25.296 --> 1:05:27.799
<i>in this cul‐de‐sac</i>
<i>along the Tennessee River,</i>

1:05:27.799 --> 1:05:32.262
then Grant will utilize
this trap perfectly

1:05:32.262 --> 1:05:35.056
<i>to fight a delaying action</i>
<i>to hold out</i>

1:05:35.056 --> 1:05:38.852
<i>until Don Carlos Buell's</i>
<i>reinforcements arrive.</i>

1:05:38.852 --> 1:05:41.896
<i>He has a whole division</i>
<i>under Lew Wallace much nearer,</i>

1:05:41.896 --> 1:05:43.773
<i>and as he goes around</i>

1:05:43.773 --> 1:05:45.441
<i>and he talks to the different</i>
<i>division commanders</i>

1:05:45.441 --> 1:05:47.735
<i>throughout the day,</i>
<i>he will tell them,</i>

1:05:47.735 --> 1:05:49.154
"Hey, Lew Wallace
is on the way.

1:05:49.154 --> 1:05:52.198
Should be here any moment now."

1:05:52.198 --> 1:05:54.033
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:05:54.033 --> 1:05:55.493
<i>‐ There's confusion</i>

1:05:55.493 --> 1:05:57.829
<i>and incoherence</i>
<i>on the battlefield,</i>

1:05:57.829 --> 1:06:00.665
but Grant had enormous
control of his emotions,

1:06:00.665 --> 1:06:04.544
so his physical courage,
this quiet competence,

1:06:04.544 --> 1:06:07.589
<i>and he was a great horseman</i>
<i>in a day and age</i>

1:06:07.589 --> 1:06:09.883
<i>when that was</i>
<i>a very important skill</i>

1:06:09.883 --> 1:06:12.177
<i>to have on the battlefield.</i>

1:06:12.177 --> 1:06:14.971
<i>‐ A number of attempts</i>
<i>were made by the enemy</i>

1:06:14.971 --> 1:06:17.849
<i>to turn our right flank</i>
<i>where Sherman was posted.</i>

1:06:19.184 --> 1:06:20.894
General Sherman, situation?

1:06:20.894 --> 1:06:22.645
‐ General.

1:06:22.645 --> 1:06:25.315
The boys bounced,
but they didn't break.

1:06:25.315 --> 1:06:28.568
I need reinforcements now.
Where's Buell?

1:06:28.568 --> 1:06:30.862
‐ No Buell.

1:06:30.862 --> 1:06:34.699
I've sent for Wallace.
Can you hold your position?

1:06:34.699 --> 1:06:38.494
‐ Yes, sir, but it'll cost.

1:06:39.871 --> 1:06:43.374
<i>‐ At the Battle of Shiloh</i>
<i>Sherman and Grant,</i>

1:06:43.374 --> 1:06:46.961
<i>while they had never been what</i>
<i>you would call good friends,</i>

1:06:46.961 --> 1:06:49.297
<i>they will first</i>
<i>come into their own</i>

1:06:49.297 --> 1:06:53.760
<i>as this wonderful duo</i>
<i>who will turn out to be</i>

1:06:53.760 --> 1:06:56.721
<i>one of the great working</i>
<i>partnerships of the war.</i>

1:06:56.721 --> 1:06:59.724
While so many other fragments
of that Union army

1:06:59.724 --> 1:07:02.352
dissolve in panicked retreat,

1:07:02.352 --> 1:07:06.606
<i>Sherman slows</i>
<i>the Confederate onslaught.</i>

1:07:06.606 --> 1:07:09.400
<i>‐ Nevertheless,</i>
<i>Grant knew that he may need</i>

1:07:09.400 --> 1:07:12.904
<i>that division of Lew Wallace's</i>
<i>to survive this fight,</i>

1:07:12.904 --> 1:07:15.990
but there's great confusion
with Wallace's division

1:07:15.990 --> 1:07:18.952
<i>on how they should get</i>
<i>to the battlefield,</i>

1:07:18.952 --> 1:07:22.747
<i>and Wallace does not show up.</i>

1:07:22.747 --> 1:07:24.415
As the Confederates
move forward,

1:07:24.415 --> 1:07:26.751
the fighting became more
and more constricted.

1:07:26.751 --> 1:07:29.921
<i>It becomes a very chaotic,</i>
<i>brutal fight,</i>

1:07:29.921 --> 1:07:32.882
<i>and Grant recognizes</i>
<i>that at points of chaos</i>

1:07:32.882 --> 1:07:34.801
<i>when everything</i>
<i>is going wrong,</i>

1:07:34.801 --> 1:07:39.430
<i>you just simply have to do</i>
<i>something to regain control.</i>

1:07:39.430 --> 1:07:43.601
‐ Grant is not gonna give up.
He's gonna stick and fight.

1:07:43.601 --> 1:07:46.479
[booming]

1:07:46.479 --> 1:07:48.147
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:07:48.147 --> 1:07:50.108
‐ Lieutenant.
‐ General Grant, sir.

1:07:50.108 --> 1:07:52.026
‐ Move your men to the left,
Lieutenant.

1:07:52.026 --> 1:07:53.444
Do it now.
‐ Yes, sir.

1:07:53.444 --> 1:07:56.447
[booming]

1:07:56.447 --> 1:07:59.659
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:07:59.659 --> 1:08:02.161
‐ Take cover!
There's too many of them!

1:08:05.039 --> 1:08:06.457
[gunfire]

1:08:06.457 --> 1:08:08.001
[all shouting]

1:08:08.001 --> 1:08:11.045
<i>[tense music]</i>

1:08:11.045 --> 1:08:18.052
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:08:18.052 --> 1:08:21.014
[gunfire]

1:08:21.014 --> 1:08:25.059
♪ ♪

1:08:25.059 --> 1:08:27.603
‐ [sentinel grunts]

1:08:27.603 --> 1:08:29.981
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:08:29.981 --> 1:08:32.233
[gunshot]

1:08:32.233 --> 1:08:37.947
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:08:37.947 --> 1:08:41.409
[screaming]

1:08:41.409 --> 1:08:44.454
<i>‐ Contrary to all my</i>
<i>experience up to that time,</i>

1:08:44.454 --> 1:08:46.789
<i>we were on the defensive.</i>

1:08:46.789 --> 1:08:48.458
<i>The endeavor of the enemy</i>

1:08:48.458 --> 1:08:51.085
<i>was simply to hurl</i>
<i>their men against ours</i>

1:08:51.085 --> 1:08:54.589
<i>with a disregard of losses</i>
<i>on their own side.</i>

1:08:54.589 --> 1:08:56.883
‐ Grant realized
he needed to buy time,

1:08:56.883 --> 1:09:00.345
or his army was about
to be overwhelmed.

1:09:00.345 --> 1:09:03.556
<i>‐ Shiloh,</i>
<i>the first day doesn't go well,</i>

1:09:03.556 --> 1:09:06.142
<i>but in the chaos, noise,</i>
<i>the friction that we know</i>

1:09:06.142 --> 1:09:08.227
<i>is inherent in a battlefield,</i>

1:09:08.227 --> 1:09:10.772
nobody gets it right initially.
Nobody.

1:09:10.772 --> 1:09:13.483
<i>Grant is able to learn</i>
<i>through hard experience,</i>

1:09:13.483 --> 1:09:16.361
and he has this vision
of how it's gonna turn out

1:09:16.361 --> 1:09:18.696
in spite of all
that's going bad around him.

1:09:18.696 --> 1:09:22.825
<i>‐ Grant is already thinking</i>
<i>to fall back gradually,</i>

1:09:22.825 --> 1:09:25.620
<i>holding successive lines</i>
<i>of defense,</i>

1:09:25.620 --> 1:09:28.831
basically trading space
for time to hold out

1:09:28.831 --> 1:09:32.502
until our reinforcements
arrive.

1:09:32.502 --> 1:09:35.463
<i>‐ And so orders went out</i>
<i>to all his division commanders</i>

1:09:35.463 --> 1:09:38.466
to hold their positions,
as Grant put it,

1:09:38.466 --> 1:09:40.843
"at all hazards."

1:09:40.843 --> 1:09:42.678
‐ What is it?

1:09:42.678 --> 1:09:45.890
‐ General Prentiss
surrendered.

1:09:45.890 --> 1:09:47.767
2,000 soldiers.

1:09:47.767 --> 1:09:50.812
<i>[tense music]</i>

1:09:50.812 --> 1:09:53.689
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:09:53.689 --> 1:09:56.359
‐ Move the artillery
to the high ground.

1:09:56.359 --> 1:09:57.694
Start the barrage at nightfall.

1:09:57.694 --> 1:10:00.488
Have the navy chip
in from the river.

1:10:00.488 --> 1:10:02.490
‐ I'll telegraph Porter.

1:10:02.490 --> 1:10:07.412
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:10:07.412 --> 1:10:11.040
<i>‐ Grant on the battlefield</i>
<i>does not appear</i>

1:10:11.040 --> 1:10:14.711
to let the demons
of failure enter.

1:10:14.711 --> 1:10:17.839
He's already been there.
He's a fighter.

1:10:17.839 --> 1:10:20.883
<i>That's one of the things</i>
<i>he brought to any army</i>

1:10:20.883 --> 1:10:24.345
<i>he was in command of,</i>
<i>was that sense of endurance,</i>

1:10:24.345 --> 1:10:27.223
<i>the sense that this isn't</i>
<i>going to be easy.</i>

1:10:27.223 --> 1:10:30.226
<i>"I'm not looking</i>
<i>to win it in a day."</i>

1:10:30.226 --> 1:10:32.937
<i>[booming]</i>

1:10:32.937 --> 1:10:36.065
<i>‐ Grant has been falling back</i>
<i>throughout the day,</i>

1:10:36.065 --> 1:10:38.901
<i>and the Confederate commander,</i>
<i>Albert Sidney Johnston,</i>

1:10:38.901 --> 1:10:40.903
wades into the battle himself

1:10:40.903 --> 1:10:43.865
<i>because he's gotta conquer</i>
<i>or perish,</i>

1:10:43.865 --> 1:10:47.744
and all of a sudden Johnston
is hit in the back of the leg,

1:10:47.744 --> 1:10:49.078
and he bleeds to death.

1:10:49.078 --> 1:10:51.914
<i>He doesn't conquer.</i>
<i>He perishes.</i>

1:10:51.914 --> 1:10:55.042
<i>‐ Johnston's second</i>
<i>in command,</i>

1:10:55.042 --> 1:10:57.253
<i>Pierre Gustave</i>
<i>Toutant Beauregard,</i>

1:10:57.253 --> 1:10:59.881
<i>took over,</i>
<i>and Beauregard believed</i>

1:10:59.881 --> 1:11:03.593
they had the Union army right
where they wanted them,

1:11:03.593 --> 1:11:07.263
<i>but Grant used the terrain</i>
<i>extraordinarily well.</i>

1:11:08.181 --> 1:11:10.099
<i>His men constructed</i>
<i>this defensive line</i>

1:11:10.099 --> 1:11:12.810
<i>along this deep ravine.</i>

1:11:12.810 --> 1:11:16.147
<i>The Confederates have to go</i>
<i>down into this ravine.</i>

1:11:16.147 --> 1:11:18.733
<i>They make one charge</i>
<i>up out of the ravine</i>

1:11:18.733 --> 1:11:22.779
<i>into this whirlwind of Union</i>
<i>artillery and musket fire.</i>

1:11:22.779 --> 1:11:26.032
<i>They are driven back</i>
<i>by this intense fire.</i>

1:11:26.032 --> 1:11:28.618
<i>Orders start to echo down</i>
<i>the Confederate line</i>

1:11:28.618 --> 1:11:30.912
<i>that we're done.</i>
<i>Stop the attack.</i>

1:11:30.912 --> 1:11:33.456
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:11:33.456 --> 1:11:34.624
Beauregard stopped the fight.

1:11:34.624 --> 1:11:36.667
"We'll finish this up
in the morning."

1:11:36.667 --> 1:11:38.628
<i>Grant,</i>
<i>sitting on horseback</i>

1:11:38.628 --> 1:11:41.464
<i>watching as the Confederates</i>
<i>fell back into the ravine,</i>

1:11:41.464 --> 1:11:45.259
<i>said, "Not beaten yet</i>
<i>by a damn sight."</i>

1:11:45.259 --> 1:11:47.804
<i>‐ Grant, with</i>
<i>this dogged determination,</i>

1:11:47.804 --> 1:11:51.808
he thinks that nobody
can beat him.

1:11:51.808 --> 1:11:54.435
<i>‐ By the time</i>
<i>darkness falls, yes,</i>

1:11:54.435 --> 1:11:57.647
<i>it's been a bad day</i>
<i>for the Union army,</i>

1:11:57.647 --> 1:12:01.275
<i>but they haven't been</i>
<i>pushed off Pittsburg Landing.</i>

1:12:01.275 --> 1:12:04.570
They're still holding on
to that strip of ground,

1:12:04.570 --> 1:12:06.322
<i>and what's more,</i>
<i>across the river</i>

1:12:06.322 --> 1:12:09.450
<i>Don Carlos Buell</i>
<i>is finally starting to arrive</i>

1:12:09.450 --> 1:12:11.953
<i>and there are federal gunboats</i>
<i>out on the river whose shells</i>

1:12:11.953 --> 1:12:16.082
<i>are keeping the Confederates</i>
<i>at bay in the darkness.</i>

1:12:17.375 --> 1:12:21.003
‐ But there were a number of
Union officers coming to Grant

1:12:21.003 --> 1:12:24.966
that night saying,
"Let's get out of here."

1:12:25.842 --> 1:12:28.636
<i>‐ Grant is almost</i>
<i>defeated on the first day,</i>

1:12:28.636 --> 1:12:31.806
<i>almost driven back</i>
<i>into the river,</i>

1:12:31.806 --> 1:12:36.519
and this is where you see Grant
at his most indomitable,

1:12:36.519 --> 1:12:39.856
in a sense‐‐most determined,
most imperturbable.

1:12:39.856 --> 1:12:42.650
<i>He is under a tree.</i>

1:12:42.650 --> 1:12:45.695
<i>He can hear</i>
<i>the cries of the wounded,</i>

1:12:45.695 --> 1:12:48.030
and Sherman comes
out of the dark.

1:12:48.030 --> 1:12:55.079
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:13:00.418 --> 1:13:03.754
‐ General Grant.
‐ Sherman.

1:13:03.754 --> 1:13:07.258
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:13:07.258 --> 1:13:10.386
‐ Well, Sam, we've had
the devil's own day,

1:13:10.386 --> 1:13:12.013
haven't we?

1:13:12.013 --> 1:13:17.268
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:13:17.268 --> 1:13:20.938
‐ Lick them tomorrow though.

1:13:20.938 --> 1:13:23.524
‐ When Wallace
and Buell turn up?

1:13:23.524 --> 1:13:25.902
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:13:25.902 --> 1:13:28.863
‐ They asked me
my plan to retreat.

1:13:28.863 --> 1:13:32.533
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:13:32.533 --> 1:13:34.952
I'll fire the first gun
in the morning.

1:13:39.582 --> 1:13:44.170
<i>[tense music]</i>

1:13:44.170 --> 1:13:46.047
<i>‐ On the second day</i>
<i>of battle,</i>

1:13:46.047 --> 1:13:47.506
<i>I gathered out parts</i>

1:13:47.506 --> 1:13:50.134
<i>of regiments</i>
<i>from troops nearby</i>

1:13:50.134 --> 1:13:52.136
<i>and marched them forward.</i>

1:13:52.136 --> 1:13:54.847
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:13:54.847 --> 1:13:57.683
<i>‐ Grant knew his army</i>
<i>was disorganized.</i>

1:13:57.683 --> 1:14:00.353
<i>They had spent a full day</i>

1:14:00.353 --> 1:14:02.730
<i>carrying out</i>
<i>this brutal fight,</i>

1:14:02.730 --> 1:14:04.857
<i>but he also suspected</i>
<i>the Confederates</i>

1:14:04.857 --> 1:14:09.111
<i>were in the same condition,</i>

1:14:09.111 --> 1:14:11.322
<i>and so he believed</i>
<i>whoever seizes the initiative</i>

1:14:11.322 --> 1:14:15.034
<i>in the morning</i>
<i>will indeed be the victor.</i>

1:14:15.034 --> 1:14:16.869
So orders went out to all
his division commanders

1:14:16.869 --> 1:14:18.746
at first light,
"begin the attack.

1:14:18.746 --> 1:14:22.917
Wherever you are with whoever
you have, begin the attack."

1:14:22.917 --> 1:14:24.752
‐ Find another commander
at Shiloh

1:14:24.752 --> 1:14:27.630
that's gonna attack on day two.

1:14:27.630 --> 1:14:28.881
Everybody else is thinking,

1:14:28.881 --> 1:14:31.217
"Oh, my goodness,
there's no way."

1:14:31.217 --> 1:14:33.928
<i>I think that Grant</i>
<i>looks at this equation</i>

1:14:33.928 --> 1:14:35.721
<i>differently than</i>
<i>everyone else.</i>

1:14:35.721 --> 1:14:39.141
<i>Grant, who's failed and had</i>
<i>to look at the dark side</i>

1:14:39.141 --> 1:14:40.977
<i>of how to be resilient,</i>

1:14:40.977 --> 1:14:42.687
<i>I think it gives him</i>
<i>an extra source of strength</i>

1:14:42.687 --> 1:14:44.271
<i>that most other commanders</i>

1:14:44.271 --> 1:14:47.358
<i>don't have the ability</i>
<i>to tap into.</i>

1:14:47.358 --> 1:14:49.735
<i>‐ He had the gift</i>
<i>of being able</i>

1:14:49.735 --> 1:14:53.447
to take in a landscape,
a map,

1:14:53.447 --> 1:14:57.368
and know almost at once
what needed to be defended,

1:14:57.368 --> 1:14:59.787
<i>what couldn't be defended,</i>

1:14:59.787 --> 1:15:02.873
<i>and what Grant</i>
<i>had seen at Shiloh</i>

1:15:02.873 --> 1:15:04.417
<i>was that the Confederates</i>

1:15:04.417 --> 1:15:05.960
<i>had exhausted</i>
<i>their last energy</i>

1:15:05.960 --> 1:15:08.504
<i>just in getting as far</i>
<i>as they had.</i>

1:15:08.504 --> 1:15:12.466
<i>Grant had seen that</i>
<i>if in the night Buell's troops</i>

1:15:12.466 --> 1:15:13.801
<i>could be ferried over</i>

1:15:13.801 --> 1:15:16.178
<i>and Grant's army</i>
<i>could be rallied</i>

1:15:16.178 --> 1:15:18.556
<i>and somehow reorganized</i>
<i>and put back into position</i>

1:15:18.556 --> 1:15:20.683
<i>for a counterattack</i>
<i>the next morning,</i>

1:15:20.683 --> 1:15:25.271
<i>then the Confederate army</i>
<i>itself would collapse.</i>

1:15:25.271 --> 1:15:28.691
<i>‐ Grant was determined</i>
<i>to stay and fight.</i>

1:15:28.691 --> 1:15:30.276
<i>Everything he's learned</i>
<i>came into play</i>

1:15:30.276 --> 1:15:34.196
<i>in making that decision.</i>

1:15:34.196 --> 1:15:38.659
That's the point
where Grant becomes Grant.

1:15:38.659 --> 1:15:41.662
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

1:15:44.498 --> 1:15:48.544
<i>‐ This day everything is</i>
<i>favorable for the Union side.</i>

1:15:48.544 --> 1:15:51.130
<i>We have now become</i>
<i>the attacking party.</i>

1:15:51.130 --> 1:15:52.757
‐ Move along!

1:15:52.757 --> 1:15:55.760
<i>[tense music]</i>

1:15:55.760 --> 1:16:00.681
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:16:00.681 --> 1:16:03.559
‐ Advance along!

1:16:03.559 --> 1:16:06.562
[all shouting]

1:16:06.562 --> 1:16:09.565
[gunfire]

1:16:09.565 --> 1:16:12.568
[booming]

1:16:12.568 --> 1:16:15.571
[all shouting]

1:16:17.907 --> 1:16:21.077
<i>[tense music]</i>

1:16:21.077 --> 1:16:28.084
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:16:28.084 --> 1:16:31.087
[all shouting]

1:16:31.087 --> 1:16:32.922
[distant gunfire]

1:16:32.922 --> 1:16:35.549
<i>‐ The enemy was driven</i>
<i>back all day,</i>

1:16:35.549 --> 1:16:39.345
<i>as we had been the day before.</i>

1:16:39.345 --> 1:16:41.055
<i>‐ It was another brutal day</i>

1:16:41.055 --> 1:16:45.184
<i>of fighting over much</i>
<i>of the same ground,</i>

1:16:45.184 --> 1:16:47.394
<i>but by 2:00 in the afternoon</i>

1:16:47.394 --> 1:16:49.230
<i>Confederate commander</i>
<i>Beauregard</i>

1:16:49.230 --> 1:16:51.649
<i>ordered a withdrawal</i>
<i>back to Corinth.</i>

1:16:51.649 --> 1:16:55.402
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:16:55.402 --> 1:16:58.864
<i>‐ The battle is over,</i>
<i>and it is,</i>

1:16:58.864 --> 1:17:02.326
<i>technically speaking,</i>
<i>a victory for the Union army.</i>

1:17:02.326 --> 1:17:06.997
It's a victory which has been
won at terrible prices.

1:17:09.208 --> 1:17:11.544
<i>‐ Huge casualties.</i>

1:17:11.544 --> 1:17:16.674
<i>25,000 killed,</i>
<i>wounded, and missing.</i>

1:17:16.674 --> 1:17:18.759
<i>This was the first time</i>
<i>in American history</i>

1:17:18.759 --> 1:17:21.428
<i>that we've seen this.</i>

1:17:21.428 --> 1:17:23.013
The armies in the revolution
and the War of 1812

1:17:23.013 --> 1:17:26.976
are smaller than
the casualty count at Shiloh.

1:17:26.976 --> 1:17:29.311
<i>‐ I saw an open field</i>
<i>on the second day</i>

1:17:29.311 --> 1:17:31.272
<i>so covered with the dead</i>

1:17:31.272 --> 1:17:33.065
<i>that it would have</i>
<i>been possible</i>

1:17:33.065 --> 1:17:36.610
<i>to walk across the clearing</i>
<i>stepping on dead bodies</i>

1:17:36.610 --> 1:17:39.196
<i>without a foot</i>
<i>touching the ground.</i>

1:17:39.196 --> 1:17:42.366
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:17:42.366 --> 1:17:44.910
[thunder rumbling]

1:17:44.910 --> 1:17:49.832
<i>‐ Shiloh itself means</i>
<i>"place of peace."</i>

1:17:49.832 --> 1:17:51.375
<i>Shiloh, for two days,</i>

1:17:51.375 --> 1:17:55.671
<i>was anything</i>
<i>but a place of peace.</i>

1:17:55.671 --> 1:18:02.052
Shiloh is incredibly important
as the place where our country

1:18:02.052 --> 1:18:06.056
woke up to the reality
of what it had signed up for.

1:18:07.474 --> 1:18:09.727
<i>It was as if</i>
<i>from the battlefield</i>

1:18:09.727 --> 1:18:13.230
<i>a metaphorical postcard</i>
<i>went home to America,</i>

1:18:13.230 --> 1:18:16.775
<i>and it said,</i>
<i>with a picture of the dead,</i>

1:18:16.775 --> 1:18:20.988
<i>"This is what</i>
<i>you've signed up for."</i>

1:18:20.988 --> 1:18:23.949
<i>It forced us to wake up.</i>

1:18:23.949 --> 1:18:26.911
<i>It forced us to grow up.</i>

1:18:26.911 --> 1:18:29.955
<i>It forced us to realize</i>
<i>that this was going</i>

1:18:29.955 --> 1:18:32.791
<i>to be much harder</i>
<i>than anybody had imagined.</i>

1:18:32.791 --> 1:18:39.882
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:19:19.338 --> 1:19:23.133
<i>‐ Up to the Battle of Shiloh,</i>
<i>I believed that the rebellion</i>

1:19:23.133 --> 1:19:26.262
<i>would collapse</i>
<i>suddenly and soon...</i>

1:19:26.262 --> 1:19:28.347
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:19:28.347 --> 1:19:33.143
<i>But after Shiloh I gave up</i>
<i>all idea of saving the Union</i>

1:19:33.143 --> 1:19:37.273
<i>except by complete conquest.</i>

1:19:37.273 --> 1:19:40.276
[flies buzzing]

1:19:40.276 --> 1:19:47.283
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:19:49.368 --> 1:19:53.664
<i>After Shiloh,</i>
<i>I was no longer boss.</i>

1:19:53.664 --> 1:19:57.251
Lincoln was right.
Vicksburg is the key.

1:19:57.251 --> 1:20:01.630
<i>The art of war</i>
<i>is simple enough.</i>

1:20:01.630 --> 1:20:03.465
<i>Find out where</i>
<i>your enemy is...</i>

1:20:03.465 --> 1:20:05.342
[all shouting]
[booming]

1:20:05.342 --> 1:20:09.054
<i>Strike him as hard as you can,</i>
<i>and keep moving on.</i>

1:20:09.054 --> 1:20:11.015
‐ You'll go after Lee.

1:20:11.015 --> 1:20:13.309
<i>You'll go after him</i>
<i>until he's finished.</i>

1:20:13.309 --> 1:20:15.644
‐ [man breathing heavily]
[gunshot]

1:20:15.644 --> 1:20:16.812
<i>‐ It all depends on you.</i>

1:20:16.812 --> 1:20:17.813
‐ [man screaming]
